# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: epigenetics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Eukaryotic chromatin consists primarily of DNA associated with histone proteins and numerous other chromatin-binding factors that contribute to genome organization and regulation.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Chromatin packages long DNA molecules into compact structures while controlling access to genetic information for processes such as transcription, DNA replication, and DNA repair.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] During cell division, chromatin facilitates proper segregation of chromosomes in anaphase; the characteristic shapes of chromosomes visible during this stage are the result of DNA being coiled into highly condensed chromatin.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Chromatin organization is often described at several structural levels.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] At the most basic level, DNA wrapped around histone octamers forms nucleosomes connected by stretches of linker DNA, producing a structure sometimes referred to as a “beads-on-a-string” fiber approximately 10–11 nm in diameter.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Nucleosome arrays can interact with each other and with linker histones to form higher-order chromatin structures.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] 30-nm chromatin fiber has been observed *in vitro*, although its presence and prevalence in living cells remain debated.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] At larger genomic scales, chromatin is organized into loops and domains that contribute to the three-dimensional architecture of the genome.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Chromosomes are further partitioned into compartments associated with active (euchromatin) or inactive (heterochromatin) chromatin states, and individual chromosomes occupy distinct spatial regions within the nucleus known as chromosome territories.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Many organisms exhibit variations in chromatin organization.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] For example, spermatozoa and avian red blood cells have more tightly packed chromatin than most eukaryotic cells.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] In contrast, some protozoa such as trypanosomatid do not DNA condense their chromatin into visible chromosomes at all.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Bacteria organize their DNA differently, forming a chromatin or nucleoid structure organized by nucleoid-associated proteins including H-NS and StpA.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Some archaeal species encode histone proteins, and package DNA into nucleosome-like assemblies of variable size, sometimes referred to as hypernucleosomes.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Chromatin organization also varies throughout the cell cycle.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] During interphase, chromatin is generally less condensed, allowing access to RNA and DNA polymerases that transcribe and replicate the DNA.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The local structure of chromatin during interphase depends on the specific genes present in the DNA.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] During mitosis and meiosis, chromatin becomes highly compacted to facilitate the segregation of chromosomes.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Within interphase nuclei, genomic regions differ in their degree of compaction and transcriptional activity.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Actively transcribed regions are often associated with less condensed chromatin known as euchromatin, whereas transcriptionally inactive or repressed regions are frequently enriched in more compact heterochromatin.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Chemical modifications of chromatin components, often so-called epigenetic modification, including histone tails methylation and acetylation also alters local chromatin structure and therefore gene expression.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The primary protein components of chromatin are histones.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Nucleosome, the fundamental basic unit of chromatin, consists of DNA wrapped around a histone octamer containing two copies each of the core histones Histone H2A, Histone H2B, Histone H3, and Histone H4.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Approximately 147 base pairs of DNA wrap around this histone octamer to form the nucleosome core particle.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Neighboring nucleosomes are connected by stretches of linker DNA, which vary in length among organisms and cell types but typically range from about 20 to 60 base pairs.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Arrays of nucleosomes connected by linker DNA form an extended fiber often described as a “beads-on-a-string” structure approximately 10–11 nm in diameter under low-salt or experimentally reconstituted conditions.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] In addition to core histones, a linker histone H1 binds near the entry and exit sites of DNA on the nucleosome and contributes to higher-order chromatin organization.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The nucleosome core particle, together with histone H1, is known as a chromatosome.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The nucleosomes bind DNA non-specifically, as required by their function in general DNA packaging.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] There are, however, large DNA sequence preferences that govern nucleosome positioning.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] This is due primarily to the varying physical properties of different DNA sequences: For instance, adenine (A), and thymine (T) is more favorably compressed into the inner minor grooves.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] This means nucleosomes can bind preferentially at one position approximately every 10 base pairs (the helical repeat of DNA)- where the DNA is rotated to maximize the number of A and T bases that will lie in the inner minor groove (see nucleic acid structure).
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Under certain experimental conditions, nucleosome arrays can fold into more compact structures with diameters of approximately 30 nm.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Early models proposed that chromatin fibers adopt regular helical arrangements, including a one-start solenoid model and a two-start zigzag model.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] However, the existence of a uniform 30-nm chromatin fiber in living cells remains debated.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Studies using cryo-electron microscopy and other high-resolution imaging methods have suggested that chromatin in many cell types forms irregular and dynamic nucleosome assemblies rather than regular 30-nm fibers.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The beads-on-a-string chromatin structure has a tendency to form loops.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] These loops allow interactions between different regions of DNA by bringing them closer to each other, which increases the efficiency of gene interactions.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] This process is dynamic, with loops forming and disappearing.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] For example, Jpx regulates the binding sites of CTCF molecules along the DNA fiber.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Chromatin compartments are large-scale structural domains of the genome that reflect the segregation of chromatin with similar transcriptional and epigenetic properties.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Genome-wide chromosome conformation capture experiments have revealed that chromosomes are partitioned into at least two major compartment types, commonly referred to as A and B compartments.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] A compartments are generally enriched in transcriptionally active chromatin, open chromatin marks, and gene-rich regions, whereas B compartments are associated with transcriptionally inactive chromatin, heterochromatin, and interactions with nuclear structures such as the nuclear lamina.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] These compartments represent preferential long-range interactions between genomic regions with similar chromatin states and contribute to the spatial organization of chromosomes within the nucleus.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Chromatin structure is highly dynamic and changes throughout the cell cycle and in response to cellular signals.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Histone proteins play a central role in organizing chromatin and can undergo a wide range of post-translational modifications, including acetylation, methylation, phosphorylation, and ubiquitination (see histone modification).
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] These modifications occur primarily on the flexible N-terminal tails of histones that extend outward from the nucleosome core.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The positively charged histone cores only partially counteract the negative charge of the DNA phosphate backbone resulting in a negative net charge of the overall structure.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] An imbalance of charge within the polymer causes electrostatic repulsion between neighboring chromatin regions that promote interactions with positively charged proteins, molecules, and cations.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] As these modifications occur, the electrostatic environment surrounding the chromatin will flux and the level of chromatin compaction will alter.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The consequences in terms of chromatin accessibility and compaction depend both on the modified amino acid and the type of modification.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Different histone modifications are associated with distinct chromatin states.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Multiple histone modifications can occur simultaneously on the same nucleosome, creating combinations of regulatory signals sometimes referred to as the *histone code*.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] For example, developmental genes in mammalian embryonic stem cells often carry both activating (H3K4me3) and repressive (H3K27me3) marks in a configuration known as bivalent structure, which is involved into cell fate transtition during early mammalian development.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Polycomb-group proteins play a role in regulating genes through modulation of chromatin structure.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Enzymes that add, remove, or recognize histone modifications are often described as chromatin writers, erasers, and readers, respectively.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] For additional information, see Chromatin variant, Histone modifications in chromatin regulation and RNA polymerase control by chromatin structure.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Chromatin and its interaction with enzymes has been researched, and a conclusion being made is that it is relevant and an important factor in gene expression.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Allfrey, a professor at Rockefeller University, stated that RNA synthesis is related to histone acetylation.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The lysine amino acid attached to the end of the histones is positively charged.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The acetylation of these tails would make the chromatin ends neutral, allowing for DNA access.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] When the chromatin decondenses, the DNA is open to entry of molecular machinery.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Fluctuations between open and closed chromatin may contribute to the discontinuity of transcription, or transcriptional bursting.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Other factors are probably involved, such as the association and dissociation of transcription factor complexes with chromatin.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Specifically, RNA polymerase and transcriptional proteins have been shown to congregate into droplets via phase separation, and recent studies have suggested that 10 nm chromatin demonstrates liquid-like behavior increasing the targetability of genomic DNA.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The interactions between linker histones and disordered tail regions act as an electrostatic glue organizing large-scale chromatin into a dynamic, liquid-like domain.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Decreased chromatin compaction comes with increased chromatin mobility and easier transcriptional access to DNA.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The phenomenon, as opposed to simple probabilistic models of transcription, can account for the high variability in gene expression occurring between cells in isogenic populations.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] DNA can adopt several conformations, most commonly referred to as A-, B-, and Z-DNA.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] B-DNA is the predominant form found under physiological conditions and is the canonical right-handed double helix described by Watson and Crick.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] A-DNA is also a right-handed helix but is more compact and is typically observed under dehydrating conditions or in certain DNA–RNA hybrid structures.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Z-DNA differs from these forms in that it is a left-handed helix with a zigzag backbone.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Transitions between B-DNA and Z-DNA can occur in regions experiencing high torsional stress, such as those generated during transcription.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Because of these properties, Z-DNA has been proposed to play roles in chromatin organization and gene regulation.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Local DNA sequence composition and structural flexibility influence how DNA interacts with histone proteins and other chromatin-associated factors.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] For example, sequences enriched in adenine and thymine can bend more easily, affecting nucleosome positioning along the genome.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The spatial arrangement of the chromatin within the nucleus is not random - specific regions of the chromatin can be found in certain territories.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Territories are, for example, the lamina-associated domains (LADs), and the topologically associating domains (TADs), which are bound together by protein complexes.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Polymer physics approaches have been widely used to model chromatin folding and genome organization.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] In particular, mechanisms such as loop extrusion, mediated by protein complexes including cohesin, have been proposed to explain the formation of chromatin loops and domain boundaries observed in chromosome conformation capture experiments.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] **Metaphase**: The metaphase structure of chromatin differs vastly to that of interphase.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] It is optimised for physical strength and manageability, forming the classic chromosome structure seen in karyotypes.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The structure of the condensed chromatin is thought to be loops of 30 nm fibre to a central scaffold of proteins.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] **Chromosome scaffolds** play an important role to hold the chromatin into compact chromosomes.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Loops of 30 nm structure further condense with scaffold, into higher order structures.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Chromosome scaffolds are made of proteins including condensin, type IIA topoisomerase and kinesin family member 4 (KIF4).
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The physical strength of chromatin is vital for this stage of division to prevent shear damage to the DNA as the daughter chromosomes are separated.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] To maximise strength the composition of the chromatin changes as it approaches the centromere, primarily through alternative histone H1 analogues.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] During mitosis, although most of the chromatin is tightly compacted, there are small regions that are not as tightly compacted.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] These regions often correspond to promoter regions of genes that were active in that cell type prior to chromatin formation.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The lack of compaction of these regions is called bookmarking, which is an epigenetic mechanism believed to be important for transmitting to daughter cells the "memory" of which genes were active prior to entry into mitosis.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] This bookmarking mechanism is needed to help transmit this memory because transcription ceases during mitosis.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] During metazoan spermiogenesis, the spermatid's chromatin is remodeled into a more spaced-packaged, widened, almost crystal-like structure.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] This process is associated with the cessation of transcription and involves nuclear protein exchange.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The histones are mostly displaced, and replaced by protamines (small, arginine-rich proteins).
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] It is proposed that in yeast, regions devoid of histones become very fragile after transcription; HMO1, an HMG-box protein, helps in stabilizing nucleosomes-free chromatin.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] A variety of internal and external agents can cause DNA damage in cells.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Many factors influence how the repair route is selected, including the cell cycle phase and chromatin segment where the break occurred.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] In terms of initiating 5' end DNA repair, the p53 binding protein 1 (53BP1) and BRCA1 are important protein components that influence double-strand break repair pathway selection.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The 53BP1 complex attaches to chromatin near DNA breaks and activates downstream factors such as Rap1-Interacting Factor 1 (RIF1) and shieldin, which protects DNA ends against nucleolytic destruction.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] DNA damage process occurs within the condition of chromatin, and the constantly changing chromatin environment has a large effect on it.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Accessing and repairing the damaged cell of DNA, the genome condenses into chromatin and repairing it through modifying the histone residues.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Through altering the chromatin structure, histones residues are adding chemical groups namely phosphate, acetyl and one or more methyl groups and these control the expressions of gene building by proteins to acquire DNA.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Moreover, resynthesis of the delighted zone, DNA will be repaired by processing and restructuring the damaged bases.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] In order to maintain genomic integrity, "homologous recombination and classical non-homologous end joining process" has been followed by DNA to be repaired.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The packaging of eukaryotic DNA into chromatin presents a barrier to all DNA-based processes that require recruitment of enzymes to their sites of action.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] To allow the critical cellular process of DNA repair, the chromatin must be remodeled.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] In eukaryotes, ATP-dependent chromatin remodeling complexes and histone-modifying enzymes are two predominant factors employed to accomplish this remodeling process.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Chromatin relaxation occurs rapidly at the site of DNA damage.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] This process is initiated by PARP1 protein that starts to appear at DNA damage in less than a second, with half maximum accumulation within 1.6 seconds after the damage occurs.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] Next the chromatin remodeler Alc1 quickly attaches to the product of PARP1, and completes arrival at the DNA damage within 10 seconds of the damage.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] About half of the maximum chromatin relaxation, presumably due to action of Alc1, occurs by 10 seconds.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] This then allows recruitment of the DNA repair enzyme MRE11, to initiate DNA repair, within 13 seconds.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] γH2AX, the phosphorylated form of H2AX is also involved in the early steps leading to chromatin decondensation after DNA damage occurrence.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The histone variant H2AX constitutes about 10% of the H2A histones in human chromatin. γH2AX (H2AX phosphorylated on serine 139) can be detected as soon as 20 seconds after irradiation of cells (with DNA double-strand break formation), and half maximum accumulation of γH2AX occurs in one minute.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The extent of chromatin with phosphorylated γH2AX is about two million base pairs at the site of a DNA double-strand break. γH2AX does not, itself, cause chromatin decondensation, but within 30 seconds of irradiation, RNF8 protein can be detected in association with γH2AX.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] RNF8 mediates extensive chromatin decondensation, through its subsequent interaction with CHD4, a component of the nucleosome remodeling and deacetylase complex NuRD.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] After undergoing relaxation subsequent to DNA damage, followed by DNA repair, chromatin recovers to a compaction state close to its pre-damage level after about 20 min.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] **DNase-seq** (DNase I hypersensitive sites Sequencing) uses the sensitivity of accessible regions in the genome to the DNase I enzyme to map open or accessible regions in the genome.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] **FAIRE-seq** (Formaldehyde-Assisted Isolation of Regulatory Elements sequencing) uses the chemical properties of protein-bound DNA in a two-phase separation method to extract nucleosome depleted regions from the genome.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] **ATAC-seq** (Assay for Transposable Accessible Chromatin sequencing) uses the Tn5 transposase to integrate (synthetic) transposons into accessible regions of the genome consequentially highlighting the localisation of nucleosomes and transcription factors across the genome.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] **DNA footprinting** is a method aimed at identifying protein-bound DNA.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] It uses labeling and fragmentation coupled to gel electrophoresis to identify areas of the genome that have been bound by proteins.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] **MNase-seq** (Micrococcal Nuclease sequencing) uses the micrococcal nuclease enzyme to identify nucleosome positioning throughout the genome.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] **Chromosome conformation capture** determines the spatial organization of chromatin in the nucleus, by inferring genomic locations that physically interact.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] **MACC profiling** (Micrococcal nuclease ACCessibility profiling) uses titration series of chromatin digests with micrococcal nuclease to identify chromatin accessibility as well as to map nucleosomes and non-histone DNA-binding proteins in both open and closed regions of the genome.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] It has been a puzzle how decondensed interphase chromosomes remain essentially unknotted.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The natural expectation is that in the presence of type II DNA topoisomerases that permit passages of double-stranded DNA regions through each other, all chromosomes should reach the state of topological equilibrium.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] The topological equilibrium in highly crowded interphase chromosomes forming chromosome territories would result in formation of highly knotted chromatin fibres.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] However, Chromosome Conformation Capture (3C) methods revealed that the decay of contacts with the genomic distance in interphase chromosomes is practically the same as in the crumpled globule state that is formed when long polymers condense without formation of any knots.
[src:epigenetics/chromatin] It has been shown that the process of chromatin-loop extrusion is ideally suited to actively unknot chromatin fibres in interphase chromosomes.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] As of 2016, two nucleobases have been found on which natural, enzymatic DNA methylation takes place: adenine and cytosine.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The modified bases are N6-methyladenine, 5-methylcytosine and N4-methylcytosine.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Methylation of cytosine to form 5-methylcytosine occurs at the same 5 position on the pyrimidine ring where the DNA base thymine's methyl group is located; the same position distinguishes thymine from the analogous RNA base uracil, which has no methyl group.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Spontaneous deamination of 5-methylcytosine converts it to thymine.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Repair mechanisms then correct it back to the original C:G pair; alternatively, they may substitute A for G, turning the original C:G pair into a T:A pair, effectively changing a base and introducing a mutation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] This misincorporated base will not be corrected during DNA replication as thymine is a DNA base.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] If the mismatch is not repaired and the cell enters the cell cycle the strand carrying the T will be complemented by an A in one of the daughter cells, such that the mutation becomes permanent.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The near-universal use of thymine exclusively in DNA and uracil exclusively in RNA may have evolved as an error-control mechanism, to facilitate the removal of uracils generated by the spontaneous deamination of cytosine.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DNA methylation as well as a number of its contemporary DNA methyltransferases (DNMT) have been thought to evolve from early world primitive RNA methylation activity and is supported by several lines of evidence.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In plants and other organisms, DNA methylation is found in three different sequence contexts: CG (or CpG), CHG or CHH (where H correspond to A, T or C).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In mammals however, DNA methylation is almost exclusively found in CpG dinucleotides, with the cytosines on both strands being usually methylated.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Non-CpG methylation can however be observed in embryonic stem cells, and has also been indicated in neural development.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Furthermore, non-CpG methylation has also been observed in hematopoietic progenitor cells, and it occurred mainly in a CpApC sequence context.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The DNA methylation landscape of vertebrates is particular compared to other organisms.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In mammals, around 75% of CpG dinucleotides are methylated in somatic cells, and DNA methylation appears as a default state that has to be specifically excluded from defined locations.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] By contrast, the genome of most plants, invertebrates, fungi, or protists show "mosaic" methylation patterns, where only specific genomic elements are targeted, and they are characterized by the alternation of methylated and unmethylated domains.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] High CpG methylation in mammalian genomes has an evolutionary cost because it increases the frequency of spontaneous mutations.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Loss of amino-groups occurs with a high frequency for cytosines, with different consequences depending on their methylation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Methylated C residues spontaneously deaminate to form T residues over time; hence CpG dinucleotides steadily deaminate to TpG dinucleotides, which is evidenced by the under-representation of CpG dinucleotides in the human genome (they occur at only 21% of the expected frequency).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In mammals, the only exception for this global CpG depletion resides in a specific category of GC- and CpG-rich sequences termed CpG islands that are generally unmethylated and therefore retained the expected CpG content.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] CpG islands are usually defined as regions with: 1) a length greater than 200bp, 2) a G+C content greater than 50%, 3) a ratio of observed to expected CpG greater than 0.6, although other definitions are sometimes used.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Excluding repeated sequences, there are around 25,000 CpG islands in the human genome, 75% of which being less than 850bp long.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] They are major regulatory units and around 50% of CpG islands are located in gene promoter regions, while another 25% lie in gene bodies, often serving as alternative promoters.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Reciprocally, around 60-70% of human genes have a CpG island in their promoter region.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The majority of CpG islands are constitutively unmethylated and enriched for permissive chromatin modification such as H3K4 methylation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In somatic tissues, only 10% of CpG islands are methylated, the majority of them being located in intergenic and intragenic regions.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DNA methylation was probably present at some extent in early eukaryote ancestors.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In virtually every organism analyzed, methylation in promoter regions correlates negatively with gene expression.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] CpG-dense promoters of actively transcribed genes are never methylated, but, reciprocally, transcriptionally silent genes do not necessarily carry a methylated promoter.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In mouse and human, around 60–70% of genes have a CpG island in their promoter region and most of these CpG islands remain unmethylated independently of the transcriptional activity of the gene, in both differentiated and undifferentiated cell types.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Of note, whereas DNA methylation of CpG islands is unambiguously linked with transcriptional repression, the function of DNA methylation in CG-poor promoters remains unclear; albeit there is little evidence that it could be functionally relevant.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DNA methylation may affect the transcription of genes in two ways.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] First, the methylation of DNA itself may physically impede the binding of transcriptional proteins to the gene, and second, and likely more important, methylated DNA may be bound by proteins known as methyl-CpG-binding domain proteins (MBDs).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] MBD proteins then recruit additional proteins to the locus, such as histone deacetylases and other chromatin remodeling proteins that can modify histones, thereby forming compact, inactive chromatin, termed heterochromatin.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] This link between DNA methylation and chromatin structure is important.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DNA methylation is a powerful transcriptional repressor, at least in CpG dense contexts.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Transcriptional repression of protein-coding genes appears essentially limited to specific classes of genes that need to be silent permanently and in almost all tissues.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] While DNA methylation does not have the flexibility required for the fine-tuning of gene regulation, its stability is perfect to ensure the permanent silencing of transposable elements.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Transposon control is one of the most ancient functions of DNA methylation that is shared by animals, plants and multiple protists.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] It is even suggested that DNA methylation evolved precisely for this purpose.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DNA methylation of transposable elements has been known to be related to genome expansion.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] However, the evolutionary driver for genome expansion remains unknown.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] There is a clear correlation between the size of the genome and CpG, suggesting that the DNA methylation of transposable elements led to a noticeable increase in the mass of DNA.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] A function that appears even more conserved than transposon silencing is positively correlated with gene expression.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In almost all species where DNA methylation is present, DNA methylation is especially enriched in the body of highly transcribed genes.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The function of gene body methylation is not well understood.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] A body of evidence suggests that it could regulate splicing and suppress the activity of intragenic transcriptional units (cryptic promoters or transposable elements).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Gene-body methylation appears closely tied to H3K36 methylation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In yeast and mammals, H3K36 methylation is highly enriched in the body of highly transcribed genes.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In yeast at least, H3K36me3 recruits enzymes such as histone deacetylases to condense chromatin and prevent the activation of cryptic start sites.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In mammals, DNMT3a and DNMT3b PWWP domain binds to H3K36me3 and the two enzymes are recruited to the body of actively transcribed genes.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DNA methylation patterns are largely erased and then re-established between generations in mammals.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Almost all of the methylations from the parents are erased, first during gametogenesis, and again in early embryogenesis, with demethylation and remethylation occurring each time.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Demethylation in early embryogenesis occurs in the preimplantation period in two stages – initially in the zygote, then during the first few embryonic replication cycles of morula and blastula.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] A wave of methylation then takes place during the implantation stage of the embryo, with CpG islands protected from methylation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] This results in global repression and allows housekeeping genes to be expressed in all cells.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In the post-implantation stage, methylation patterns are stage- and tissue-specific, with changes that would define each individual cell type lasting stably over a long period.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Studies on rat limb buds during embryogenesis have further illustrated the dynamic nature of DNA methylation in development.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In this context, variations in global DNA methylation were observed across different developmental stages and culture conditions, highlighting the intricate regulation of methylation during organogenesis and its potential implications for regenerative medicine strategies.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Whereas DNA methylation is not necessary *per se* for transcriptional silencing, it is thought nonetheless to represent a "locked" state that definitely inactivates transcription.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In particular, DNA methylation appears critical for the maintenance of mono-allelic silencing in the context of genomic imprinting and X chromosome inactivation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In these cases, expressed and silent alleles differ by their methylation status, and loss of DNA methylation results in loss of imprinting and re-expression of Xist in somatic cells.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] During embryonic development, few genes change their methylation status, at the important exception of a number of genes specifically expressed in the germline.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DNA methylation appears absolutely required in differentiated cells, as knockout of any of the three competent DNA methyltransferase results in embryonic or post-partum lethality.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] By contrast, DNA methylation is dispensable in undifferentiated cell types, such as the inner cell mass of the blastocyst, primordial germ cells or embryonic stem cells.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Since DNA methylation appears to directly regulate only a limited number of genes, how precisely DNA methylation absence causes the death of differentiated cells remain an open question.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Due to the phenomenon of genomic imprinting, maternal and paternal genomes are differentially marked and must be properly reprogrammed every time they pass through the germline.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Therefore, during gametogenesis, primordial germ cells must have their original biparental DNA methylation patterns erased and re-established based on the sex of the transmitting parent.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] After fertilization, the paternal and maternal genomes are once again demethylated and remethylated (except for differentially methylated regions associated with imprinted genes).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] This reprogramming is likely required for totipotency of the newly formed embryo and erasure of acquired epigenetic changes.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In multiple disease processes, such as cancer, gene promoter CpG islands acquire abnormal hypermethylation, which results in transcriptional silencing that can be inherited by daughter cells following cell division.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Alterations of DNA methylation have been recognized as an important component of cancer development.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Hypomethylation, in general, arises earlier and is linked to chromosomal instability and loss of imprinting, whereas hypermethylation is associated with promoters and can arise secondary to gene (oncogene suppressor) silencing, but might be a target for epigenetic therapy.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In developmental contexts, dynamic changes in DNA methylation patterns also have significant implications.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] For instance, in rat limb buds, shifts in methylation status were associated with different stages of chondrogenesis, suggesting a potential link between DNA methylation and the progression of certain developmental processes.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Global hypomethylation has also been implicated in the development and progression of cancer through different mechanisms.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Typically, there is hypermethylation of tumor suppressor genes and hypomethylation of oncogenes.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Generally, in progression to cancer, hundreds of genes are silenced or activated.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Although silencing of some genes in cancers occurs by mutation, a large proportion of carcinogenic gene silencing is a result of altered DNA methylation (see DNA methylation in cancer).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DNA methylation causing silencing in cancer typically occurs at multiple CpG sites in the CpG islands that are present in the promoters of protein coding genes.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Altered expressions of microRNAs also silence or activate multiple genes in progression to cancer (see microRNAs in cancer).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Altered microRNA expression occurs through hyper/hypo-methylation of CpG sites in CpG islands in promoters controlling transcription of the microRNAs.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Silencing of DNA repair genes through methylation of CpG islands in their promoters appears to be especially important in progression to cancer (see methylation of DNA repair genes in cancer).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Epigenetic modifications such as DNA methylation have been implicated in cardiovascular disease, including atherosclerosis.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In animal models of atherosclerosis, vascular tissue, as well as blood cells such as mononuclear blood cells, exhibit global hypomethylation with gene-specific areas of hypermethylation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DNA methylation polymorphisms may be used as an early biomarker of atherosclerosis since they are present before lesions are observed, which may provide an early tool for detection and risk prevention.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Two of the cell types targeted for DNA methylation polymorphisms are monocytes and lymphocytes, which experience an overall hypomethylation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] One proposed mechanism behind this global hypomethylation is elevated homocysteine levels causing hyperhomocysteinemia, a known risk factor for cardiovascular disease.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] High plasma levels of homocysteine inhibit DNA methyltransferases, which causes hypomethylation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Hypomethylation of DNA affects genes that alter smooth muscle cell proliferation, cause endothelial cell dysfunction, and increase inflammatory mediators, all of which are critical in forming atherosclerotic lesions.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] High levels of homocysteine also result in hypermethylation of CpG islands in the promoter region of the estrogen receptor alpha (ERα) gene, causing its down regulation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] ERα protects against atherosclerosis due to its action as a growth suppressor, causing the smooth muscle cells to remain in a quiescent state.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Hypermethylation of the ERα promoter thus allows intimal smooth muscle cells to proliferate excessively and contribute to the development of the atherosclerotic lesion.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Another gene that experiences a change in methylation status in atherosclerosis is the monocarboxylate transporter (MCT3), which produces a protein responsible for the transport of lactate and other ketone bodies out of a number of cell types, including vascular smooth muscle cells.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In atherosclerosis patients, there is an increase in methylation of the CpG islands in exon 2, which decreases MCT3 protein expression.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The downregulation of MCT3 impairs lactate transport and significantly increases smooth muscle cell proliferation, which further contributes to the atherosclerotic lesion.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] An ex vivo experiment using the demethylating agent Decitabine (5-aza-2 -deoxycytidine) was shown to induce MCT3 expression in a dose dependent manner, as all hypermethylated sites in the exon 2 CpG island became demethylated after treatment.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] This may serve as a novel therapeutic agent to treat atherosclerosis, although no human studies have been conducted thus far.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In addition to atherosclerosis described above, specific epigenetic changes have been identified in the failing human heart.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] For example, in ischemic heart failure DNA methylation changes have been linked to changes in gene expression that may direct gene expression associated with the changes in heart metabolism known to occur.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Additional forms of heart failure (e.g. diabetic cardiomyopathy) and co-morbidities (e.g. obesity) must be explored to see how common these mechanisms are.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Most strikingly, in failing human heart these changes in DNA methylation are associated with racial and socioeconomic status which further impact how gene expression is altered, and may influence how the individual's heart failure should be treated.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In humans and other mammals, DNA methylation levels can be used to accurately estimate the age of tissues and cell types, forming an accurate epigenetic clock.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] A longitudinal study of twin children showed that, between the ages of 5 and 10, there was divergence of methylation patterns due to environmental rather than genetic influences.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] There is a global loss of DNA methylation during aging.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In a study that analyzed the complete DNA methylomes of CD4+ T cells in a newborn, a 26 years old individual and a 103 years old individual were observed that the loss of methylation is proportional to age.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Hypomethylated CpGs observed in the centenarian DNAs compared with the neonates covered all genomic compartments (promoters, intergenic, intronic and exonic regions).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] High intensity exercise has been shown to result in reduced DNA methylation in skeletal muscle.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Promoter methylation of PGC-1α and PDK4 were immediately reduced after high intensity exercise, whereas PPAR-δ methylation was not reduced until three hours after exercise.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] At the same time, six months of exercise in previously sedentary middle-age men resulted in increased methylation in adipose tissue.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] One study showed a possible increase in global genomic DNA methylation of white blood cells with more physical activity in non-Hispanics.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] A study that investigated the methylome of B cells along their differentiation cycle, using whole-genome bisulfite sequencing (WGBS), showed that there is a hypomethylation from the earliest stages to the most differentiated stages.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The largest methylation difference is between the stages of germinal center B cells and memory B cells.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Furthermore, this study showed that there is a similarity between B cell tumors and long-lived B cells in their DNA methylation signatures.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Two reviews summarize evidence that DNA methylation alterations in brain neurons are important in learning and memory.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Contextual fear conditioning (a form of associative learning) in animals, such as mice and rats, is rapid and is extremely robust in creating memories.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In mice and in rats contextual fear conditioning, within 1–24 hours, it is associated with altered methylations of several thousand DNA cytosines in genes of hippocampus neurons.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Twenty four hours after contextual fear conditioning, 9.2% of the genes in rat hippocampus neurons are differentially methylated.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In mice, when examined at four weeks after conditioning, the hippocampus methylations and demethylations had been reset to the original naive conditions.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The hippocampus is needed to form memories, but memories are not stored there.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] For such mice, at four weeks after contextual fear conditioning, substantial differential CpG methylations and demethylations occurred in cortical neurons during memory maintenance, and there were 1,223 differentially methylated genes in their anterior cingulate cortex.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Mechanisms guiding new DNA methylations and new DNA demethylations in the hippocampus during memory establishment were summarized in 2022.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] That review also indicated the mechanisms by which the new patterns of methylation gave rise to new patterns of messenger RNA expression.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] These new messenger RNAs were then transported by messenger RNP particles (neuronal granules) to synapses of the neurons, where they could be translated into proteins.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Active changes in neuronal DNA methylation and demethylation appear to act as controllers of synaptic scaling and glutamate receptor trafficking in learning and memory formation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In mammalian cells, DNA methylation occurs mainly at the C5 position of CpG dinucleotides and is carried out by two general classes of enzymatic activities – maintenance methylation and *de novo* methylation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Maintenance methylation activity is necessary to preserve DNA methylation after every cellular DNA replication cycle.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Without the DNA methyltransferase (DNMT), the replication machinery itself would produce daughter strands that are unmethylated and, over time, would lead to passive demethylation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DNMT1 is the proposed maintenance methyltransferase that is responsible for copying DNA methylation patterns to the daughter strands during DNA replication.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Mouse models with both copies of DNMT1 deleted are embryonic lethal at approximately day 9, due to the requirement of DNMT1 activity for development in mammalian cells.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] It is thought that DNMT3A and DNMT3B are the *de novo* methyltransferases that set up DNA methylation patterns early in development.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DNMT3L is a protein that is homologous to the other DNMT3s but has no catalytic activity.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Instead, DNMT3L assists the *de novo* methyltransferases by increasing their ability to bind to DNA and stimulating their activity.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Mice and rats have a third functional *de novo* methyltransferase enzyme named DNMT3C, which evolved as a paralog of *Dnmt3b* by tandem duplication in the common ancestral of Muroidea rodents.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DNMT3C catalyzes the methylation of promoters of transposable elements during early spermatogenesis, an activity shown to be essential for their epigenetic repression and male fertility.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] It is yet unclear if other mammals that do not have DNMT3C (like humans) rely on DNMT3B or DNMT3A for *de novo* methylation of transposable elements in the germline.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Finally, DNMT2 (TRDMT1) has been identified as a DNA methyltransferase homolog, containing all 10 sequence motifs common to all DNA methyltransferases; however, DNMT2 (TRDMT1) does not methylate DNA but instead methylates cytosine-38 in the anticodon loop of aspartic acid transfer RNA.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Since some tumor suppressor genes are silenced by DNA methylation during carcinogenesis, there have been attempts to re-express these genes by inhibiting the DNMTs.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] 5-Aza-2'-deoxycytidine (decitabine) is a nucleoside analog that inhibits DNMTs by trapping them in a covalent complex on DNA by preventing the β-elimination step of catalysis, thus resulting in the enzymes' degradation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] However, for decitabine to be active, it must be incorporated into the genome of the cell, which can cause mutations in the daughter cells if the cell does not die.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In addition, decitabine is toxic to the bone marrow, which limits the size of its therapeutic window.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] These pitfalls have led to the development of antisense RNA therapies that target the DNMTs by degrading their mRNAs and preventing their translation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] However, it is currently unclear whether targeting DNMT1 alone is sufficient to reactivate tumor suppressor genes silenced by DNA methylation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Significant progress has been made in understanding DNA methylation in the model plant *Arabidopsis thaliana*.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DNA methylation in plants differs from that of mammals: while DNA methylation in mammals mainly occurs on the cytosine nucleotide in a CpG site, in plants the cytosine can be methylated at CpG, CpHpG, and CpHpH sites, where H represents any nucleotide but not guanine.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Overall, *Arabidopsis* DNA is highly methylated, mass spectrometry analysis estimated 14% of cytosines to be modified.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Later, bisulfite sequencing data estimated that around 25% of *Arabidopsis* CG sites are methylated, but these levels vary based on the geographic location of *Arabidopsis* accessions (plants in the north are more highly methylated than southern accessions).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The principal *Arabidopsis* DNA methyltransferase enzymes, which transfer and covalently attach methyl groups onto DNA, are DRM2, MET1, and CMT3.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Both the DRM2 and MET1 proteins share significant homology to the mammalian methyltransferases DNMT3 and DNMT1, respectively, whereas the CMT3 protein is unique to the plant kingdom.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DRM2 is the only enzyme that has been implicated as a *de novo* DNA methyltransferase.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DRM2 has also been shown, along with MET1 and CMT3 to be involved in maintaining methylation marks through DNA replication.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Other DNA methyltransferases are expressed in plants but have no known function (see the Chromatin Database).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Genome-wide levels of DNA methylation vary widely between plant species, and *Arabidopsis* cytosines tend to be less densely methylated than those in other plants.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] For example, ~92.5% of CpG cytosines are methylated in *Beta vulgaris*.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The patterns of methylation also differ between cytosine sequence contexts; universally, CpG methylation is higher than CHG and CHH methylation, and CpG methylation can be found in both active genes and transposable elements, while CHG and CHH are usually relegated to silenced transposable elements.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] It is not clear how the cell determines the locations of *de novo* DNA methylation, but evidence suggests that for some locations, RNA-directed DNA methylation (RdDM) is involved.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In RdDM, specific RNA transcripts are produced from a genomic DNA template, and this RNA forms secondary structures called double-stranded RNA molecules.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The double-stranded RNAs, through either the small interfering RNA (siRNA) or microRNA (miRNA) pathways direct de-novo DNA methylation of the original genomic location that produced the RNA.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] This sort of mechanism is thought to be important in cellular defense against RNA viruses and/or transposons, both of which often form a double-stranded RNA that can be mutagenic to the host genome.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] By methylating their genomic locations, through an as yet poorly understood mechanism, they are shut off and are no longer active in the cell, protecting the genome from their mutagenic effect.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Recently, it was described that methylation of the DNA is the main determinant of embryogenic cultures formation from explants in woody plants and is regarded the main mechanism that explains the poor response of mature explants to somatic embryogenesis in the plants (Isah 2016).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Diverse orders of insects show varied patterns of DNA methylation, from almost undetectable levels in flies to low levels in butterflies and higher in true bugs and some cockroaches (up to 14% of all CG sites in *Blattella asahinai*).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Functional DNA methylation has been discovered in Honey Bees.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Many fungi have low levels (0.1 to 0.5%) of cytosine methylation, whereas other fungi have as much as 5% of the genome methylated.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] This value seems to vary both among species and among isolates of the same species.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] There is also evidence that DNA methylation may be involved in state-specific control of gene expression in fungi.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] However, at a detection limit of 250 attomoles by using ultra-high sensitive mass spectrometry DNA methylation was not confirmed in single cellular yeast species such as *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* or *Schizosaccharomyces pombe*, indicating that yeasts do not possess this DNA modification.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Although brewers' yeast (*Saccharomyces*), fission yeast (*Schizosaccharomyces*), and *Aspergillus flavus* have no detectable DNA methylation, the model filamentous fungus *Neurospora crassa* has a well-characterized methylation system.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Several genes control methylation in *Neurospora* and mutation of the DNA methyl transferase, *dim-2*, eliminates all DNA methylation but does not affect growth or sexual reproduction.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] While the *Neurospora* genome has little repeated DNA, half of the methylation occurs in repeated DNA including transposon relics and centromeric DNA.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The ability to evaluate other important phenomena in a DNA methylase-deficient genetic background makes *Neurospora* an important system in which to study DNA methylation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DNA methylation is largely absent from *Dictyostelium discoideum* where it appears to occur at about 0.006% of cytosines.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Adenine or cytosine methylation are mediated by restriction modification systems of a number of bacteria, in which specific DNA sequences are methylated periodically throughout the genome.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] A methylase is the enzyme that recognizes a specific sequence and methylates one of the bases in or near that sequence.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Foreign DNAs (which are not methylated in this manner) that are introduced into the cell are degraded by sequence-specific restriction enzymes and cleaved.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Bacterial genomic DNA is not recognized by these restriction enzymes.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The methylation of native DNA acts as a sort of primitive immune system, allowing the bacteria to protect themselves from infection by bacteriophage.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] One region of the DNA that keeps its hemimethylated status for longer is the origin of replication, which has an abundance of GATC sites.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] This is central to the bacterial mechanism for timing DNA replication.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] SeqA binds to the origin of replication, sequestering it and thus preventing methylation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Because hemimethylated origins of replication are inactive, this mechanism limits DNA replication to once per cell cycle.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Expression of certain genes, for example, those coding for pilus expression in *E. coli*, is regulated by the methylation of GATC sites in the promoter region of the gene operon.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The cells' environmental conditions just after DNA replication determine whether Dam is blocked from methylating a region proximal to or distal from the promoter region.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Once the pattern of methylation has been created, the pilus gene transcription is locked in the on or off position until the DNA is again replicated.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In *E. coli*, these pili operons have important roles in virulence in urinary tract infections.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] It has been proposed that inhibitors of Dam may function as antibiotics.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] On the other hand, DNA cytosine methylase targets CCAGG and CCTGG sites to methylate cytosine at the C5 position (C meC(A/T) GG).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The other methylase enzyme, EcoKI, causes methylation of adenines in the sequences AAC(N6)GTGC and GCAC(N6)GTT.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In *Clostridioides difficile*, DNA methylation at the target motif CAAAAA was shown to impact sporulation, a key step in disease transmission, as well as cell length, biofilm formation and host colonization.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Most strains used by molecular biologists are derivatives of *E. coli* K-12, and possess both Dam and Dcm, but there are commercially available strains that are dam-/dcm- (lack of activity of either methylase).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In fact, it is possible to unmethylate the DNA extracted from dam+/dcm+ strains by transforming it into dam-/dcm- strains.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] This would help digest sequences that are not being recognized by methylation-sensitive restriction enzymes.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The restriction enzyme DpnI can recognize 5'-GmeATC-3' sites and digest the methylated DNA.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Being such a short motif, it occurs frequently in sequences by chance, and as such its primary use for researchers is to degrade template DNA following PCRs (PCR products lack methylation, as no methylases are present in the reaction).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Similarly, some commercially available restriction enzymes are sensitive to methylation at their cognate restriction sites and must as mentioned previously be used on DNA passed through a dam-/dcm- strain to allow cutting.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Differentially methylated regions, which are genomic regions with different methylation statuses among multiple samples (tissues, cells, individuals or others), are regarded as possible functional regions involved in gene transcriptional regulation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The identification of DMRs among multiple tissues (T-DMRs) provides a comprehensive survey of epigenetic differences among human tissues.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] For example, these methylated regions that are unique to a particular tissue allow individuals to differentiate between tissue type, such as semen and vaginal fluid.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Current research conducted by Lee et al., showed DACT1 and USP49 positively identified semen by examining T-DMRs.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The use of T-DMRs has proven useful in the identification of various body fluids found at crime scenes.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Researchers in the forensic field are currently seeking novel T-DMRs in genes to use as markers in forensic DNA analysis.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] DMRs between cancer and normal samples (C-DMRs) demonstrate the aberrant methylation in cancers.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] It is well known that DNA methylation is associated with cell differentiation and proliferation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Multiple DMRs have been found in the development stages (D-DMRs) and in the reprogrammed progress (R-DMRs).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] In addition, there are intra-individual DMRs (Intra-DMRs) with longitudinal changes in global DNA methylation along with the increase of age in a given individual.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] There are also inter-individual DMRs (Inter-DMRs) with different methylation patterns among multiple individuals.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] QDMR (Quantitative Differentially Methylated Regions) is a quantitative approach to quantify methylation difference and identify DMRs from genome-wide methylation profiles by adapting Shannon entropy.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] The platform-free and species-free nature of QDMR makes it potentially applicable to various methylation data.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] This approach provides an effective tool for the high-throughput identification of the functional regions involved in epigenetic regulation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] QDMR can be used as an effective tool for the quantification of methylation difference and identification of DMRs across multiple samples.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p01] Gene-set analysis (a.k.a. pathway analysis; usually performed tools such as DAVID, GoSeq or GSEA) has been shown to be severely biased when applied to high-throughput methylation data (e.g.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] DNA methylation marks – genomic regions with specific methylation patterns in a specific biological state such as tissue, cell type, individual – are regarded as possible functional regions involved in gene transcriptional regulation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] Although various human cell types may have the same genome, these cells have different methylomes.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] The systematic identification and characterization of methylation marks across cell types are crucial to understanding the complex regulatory network for cell fate determination.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] Hongbo Liu et al. proposed an entropy-based framework termed SMART to integrate the whole genome bisulfite sequencing methylomes across 42 human tissues/cells and identified 757,887 genome segments.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] Nearly 75% of the segments showed uniform methylation across all cell types.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] From the remaining 25% of the segments, they identified cell type-specific hypo/hypermethylation marks that were specifically hypo/hypermethylated in a minority of cell types using a statistical approach and presented an atlas of the human methylation marks.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] Further analysis revealed that the cell type-specific hypomethylation marks were enriched through H3K27ac and transcription factor binding sites in a cell type-specific manner.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] In particular, they observed that the cell type-specific hypomethylation marks are associated with the cell type-specific super-enhancers that drive the expression of cell identity genes.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] This framework provides a complementary, functional annotation of the human genome and helps to elucidate the critical features and functions of cell type-specific hypomethylation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] The entropy-based Specific Methylation Analysis and Report Tool, termed "SMART", which focuses on integrating a large number of DNA methylomes for the de novo identification of cell type-specific methylation marks.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] The latest version of SMART is focused on three main functions including de novo identification of differentially methylated regions (DMRs) by genome segmentation, identification of DMRs from predefined regions of interest, and identification of differentially methylated CpG sites.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] DNA methylation allows for several tissues to be analyzed in one assay as well as for small amounts of body fluid to be identified with the use of extracted DNA.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] Usually, the two approaches of DNA methylation are either methylated-sensitive restriction enzymes or treatment with sodium bisulphite.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] Methylated sensitive restriction enzymes work by cleaving specific CpG, cytosine and guanine separated by only one phosphate group, recognition sites when the CpG is methylated.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] In contrast, unmethylated cytosines are transformed to uracil and in the process, methylated cytosines remain methylated.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] In particular, methylation profiles can provide insight on when or how body fluids were left at crime scenes, identify the kind of body fluid, and approximate age, gender, and phenotypic characteristics of perpetrators.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] Research indicates various markers that can be used for DNA methylation.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] Deciding which marker to use for an assay is one of the first steps of the identification of body fluids.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] In general, markers are selected by examining prior research conducted.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] Identification markers that are chosen should give a positive result for one type of cell.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] One portion of the chromosome that is an area of focus when conducting DNA methylation are tissue-specific differentially methylated regions, T-DMRs.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] The degree of methylation for the T-DMRs ranges depending on the body fluid.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] A research team developed a marker system that is two-fold.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] The first marker is methylated only in the target fluid while the second is methylated in the rest of the fluids.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] For instance, if venous blood marker A is un-methylated and venous blood marker B is methylated in a fluid, it indicates the presence of only venous blood.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] In contrast, if venous blood marker A is methylated and venous blood marker B is un-methylated in some fluid, then that indicates venous blood is in a mixture of fluids.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] Some examples for DNA methylation markers are Mens1(menstrual blood), Spei1(saliva), and Sperm2(seminal fluid).
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] DNA methylation provides a relatively good means of sensitivity when identifying and detecting body fluids.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] In one study, only ten nanograms of a sample was necessary to ascertain successful results.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] DNA methylation provides a good discernment of mixed samples since it involves markers that give "on or off" signals.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] DNA methylation is not impervious to external conditions.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] Even under degraded conditions using the DNA methylation techniques, the markers are stable enough that there are still noticeable differences between degraded samples and control samples.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] Specifically, in one study, it was found that there were not any noticeable changes in methylation patterns over an extensive period of time.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] The detection of DNA methylation in cell-free DNA and other body fluids has recently become one of the main approaches to Liquid biopsy.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] In particular, the identification of tissue-specific and disease-specific patterns allows for non-invasive detection and monitoring of diseases such as cancer.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] If compared to strictly genomic approaches to liquid biopsy, DNA methylation profiling offers a larger number of differentially methylated CpG sites and differentially methylated regions (DMRSs), potentially enhancing its sensitivity.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] Signal deconvolution algorithms based on DNA methylation have been successfully applied to cell-free DNA and can nominate the tissue of origin of cancers of unknown primary, allograft rejection, and resistance to hormone therapy.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] DNA methylation can also be detected by computational models through sophisticated algorithms and methods.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] Computational models can facilitate the global profiling of DNA methylation across chromosomes, and often such models are faster and cheaper to perform than biological assays.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] Such up-to-date computational models include Bhasin, *et al.*, Bock, *et al*., and Zheng, *et al*.
[src:epigenetics/dna-methylation-p02] Together with biological assay, these methods greatly facilitate the DNA methylation analysis.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The term also refers to the mechanism behind these changes: functionally relevant alterations to the genome that do not involve mutations in the nucleotide sequence.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Examples of mechanisms that produce such changes are DNA methylation and histone modification, each of which alters how genes are expressed without altering the underlying DNA sequence.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Further, non-coding RNA sequences have been shown to play a key role in the regulation of gene expression.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Gene expression can be controlled through the action of repressor proteins that attach to silencer regions of the DNA.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] One example of an epigenetic change in eukaryotic biology is the process of cellular differentiation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] During morphogenesis, totipotent stem cells become the various pluripotent cell lines of the embryo, which in turn become fully differentiated cells.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The term *epigenesis* has a generic meaning of "extra growth" that has been used in English since the 17th century.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In scientific publications, the term *epigenetics* started to appear in the 1930s (see Fig. on the right).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] However, its contemporary meaning emerged only in the 1990s.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The hypothesis of epigenetic changes affecting the expression of chromosomes was put forth by the Russian biologist Nikolai Koltsov.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] From the generic meaning, and the associated adjective *epigenetic*, British embryologist C.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Waddington coined the term *epigenetics* in 1942 as pertaining to *epigenesis*, in parallel to Valentin Haecker's 'phenogenetics' (*Phänogenetik*).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] *Epigenesis* in the context of the biology of that period referred to the differentiation of cells from their initial totipotent state during embryonic development.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] When Waddington coined the term, the physical nature of genes and their role in heredity was not known.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] He used it instead as a conceptual model of how genetic components might interact with their surroundings to produce a phenotype; he used the phrase "epigenetic landscape" as a metaphor for biological development.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Waddington held that cell fates were established during development in a process he called canalisation much as a marble rolls down to the point of lowest local elevation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Waddington suggested visualising increasing irreversibility of cell type differentiation as ridges rising between the valleys where the marbles (analogous to cells) are travelling.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In recent times, Waddington's notion of the epigenetic landscape has been rigorously formalized in the context of the systems dynamics state approach to the study of cell-fate.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Cell-fate determination is predicted to exhibit certain dynamics, such as attractor-convergence (the attractor can be an equilibrium point, limit cycle or strange attractor) or oscillatory.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] More recent usage of the word in biology follows stricter definitions.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The term has also been used, however, to describe processes which have not been demonstrated to be heritable, such as some forms of histone modification.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Consequently, there are attempts to redefine "epigenetics" in broader terms that would avoid the constraints of requiring heritability.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Such redefinitions however are not universally accepted and are still subject to debate.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The similarity of the word to "genetics" has generated many parallel usages.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The "epigenome" is a parallel to the word "genome", referring to the overall epigenetic state of a cell, and epigenomics refers to global analyses of epigenetic changes across the entire genome.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The phrase "genetic code" has also been adapted – the "epigenetic code" has been used to describe the set of epigenetic features that create different phenotypes in different cells from the same underlying DNA sequence.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Taken to its extreme, the "epigenetic code" could represent the total state of the cell, with the position of each molecule accounted for in an *epigenomic map*, a diagrammatic representation of the gene expression, DNA methylation and histone modification status of a particular genomic region.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] More typically, the term is used in reference to systematic efforts to measure specific, relevant forms of epigenetic information such as the histone code or DNA methylation patterns.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Therefore, the word "epigenetics" is sometimes used as a synonym for these processes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Chromatin remodeling is not always inherited, and not all epigenetic inheritance involves chromatin remodeling.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In 2019, a further lysine modification appeared in the scientific literature linking epigenetics modification to cell metabolism, i.e. lactylation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Because the phenotype of a cell or individual is affected by which of its genes are transcribed, heritable transcription states can give rise to epigenetic effects.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] There are several layers of regulation of gene expression.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] One way that genes are regulated is through the remodeling of chromatin.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Chromatin is the complex of DNA and the histone proteins with which it associates.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] If the way that DNA is wrapped around the histones changes, gene expression can change as well.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The second way is the addition of methyl groups to the DNA, mostly at CpG sites, to convert cytosine to 5-methylcytosine.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] 5-Methylcytosine performs much like a regular cytosine, pairing with a guanine in double-stranded DNA.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] However, when methylated cytosines are present in CpG sites in the promoter and enhancer regions of genes, the genes are often repressed.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] When methylated cytosines are present in CpG sites in the gene body (in the coding region excluding the transcription start site) expression of the gene is often enhanced.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Transcription of a gene usually depends on a transcription factor binding to a (10 base or less) recognition sequence at the enhancer that interacts with the promoter region of that gene (Gene expression#Enhancers, transcription factors, mediator complex and DNA loops in mammalian transcription).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] About 22% of transcription factors are inhibited from binding when the recognition sequence has a methylated cytosine.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In addition, presence of methylated cytosines at a promoter region can attract methyl-CpG-binding domain (MBD) proteins.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] All MBDs interact with nucleosome remodeling and histone deacetylase complexes, which leads to gene silencing.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In addition, another covalent modification involving methylated cytosine is its demethylation by TET enzymes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Hundreds of such demethylations occur, for instance, during learning and memory forming events in neurons.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] There is frequently a reciprocal relationship between DNA methylation and histone lysine methylation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] For instance, the methyl binding domain protein MBD1, attracted to and associating with methylated cytosine in a DNA CpG site, can also associate with H3K9 methyltransferase activity to methylate histone 3 at lysine 9.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] On the other hand, DNA maintenance methylation by DNMT1 appears to partly rely on recognition of histone methylation on the nucleosome present at the DNA site to carry out cytosine methylation on newly synthesized DNA.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] There is further crosstalk between DNA methylation carried out by DNMT3A and DNMT3B and histone methylation so that there is a correlation between the genome-wide distribution of DNA methylation and histone methylation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Mechanisms of heritability of histone state are not well understood; however, much is known about the mechanism of heritability of DNA methylation state during cell division and differentiation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Heritability of methylation state depends on certain enzymes (such as DNMT1) that have a higher affinity for 5-methylcytosine than for cytosine.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] If this enzyme reaches a "hemimethylated" portion of DNA (where 5-methylcytosine is in only one of the two DNA strands) the enzyme will methylate the other half.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] However, it is now known that DNMT1 physically interacts with the protein UHRF1.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] UHRF1 has been recently recognized as essential for DNMT1-mediated maintenance of DNA methylation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] UHRF1 is the protein that specifically recognizes hemi-methylated DNA, therefore bringing DNMT1 to its substrate to maintain DNA methylation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The lysines (K) are designated with a number showing their position as, for instance (K4), indicating lysine as the 4th amino acid from the amino (N) end of the tail in the histone protein.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Although histone modifications occur throughout the entire sequence, the unstructured N-termini of histones (called histone tails) are particularly highly modified.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] These modifications include acetylation, methylation, ubiquitylation, phosphorylation, sumoylation, ribosylation and citrullination.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Acetylation is the most highly studied of these modifications.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] For example, acetylation of the K14 and K9 lysines of the tail of histone H3 by histone acetyltransferase enzymes (HATs) is generally related to transcriptional competence (see Figure).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] One mode of thinking is that this tendency of acetylation to be associated with "active" transcription is biophysical in nature.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Because it normally has a positively charged nitrogen at its end, lysine can bind the negatively charged phosphates of the DNA backbone.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The acetylation event converts the positively charged amine group on the side chain into a neutral amide linkage.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] This removes the positive charge, thus loosening the DNA from the histone.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] When this occurs, complexes like SWI/SNF and other transcriptional factors can bind to the DNA and allow transcription to occur.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] This is the "cis" model of the epigenetic function.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In other words, changes to the histone tails have a direct effect on the DNA itself.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Another model of epigenetic function is the "trans" model.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In this model, changes to the histone tails act indirectly on the DNA.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] For example, lysine acetylation may create a binding site for chromatin-modifying enzymes (or transcription machinery as well).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] This chromatin remodeler can then cause changes to the state of the chromatin.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Indeed, a bromodomain – a protein domain that specifically binds acetyl-lysine – is found in many enzymes that help activate transcription, including the SWI/SNF complex.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] It may be that acetylation acts in this and the previous way to aid in transcriptional activation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The idea that modifications act as docking modules for related factors is borne out by histone methylation as well.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Methylation of lysine 9 of histone H3 has long been associated with constitutively transcriptionally silent chromatin (constitutive heterochromatin) (see bottom Figure).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] It has been determined that a chromodomain (a domain that specifically binds methyl-lysine) in the transcriptionally repressive protein HP1 recruits HP1 to K9 methylated regions.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] One example that seems to refute this biophysical model for methylation is that tri-methylation of histone H3 at lysine 4 is strongly associated with (and required for full) transcriptional activation (see top Figure).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Tri-methylation, in this case, would introduce a fixed positive charge on the tail.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] It has been shown that the histone lysine methyltransferase (KMT) is responsible for this methylation activity in the pattern of histones H3 & H4.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] This enzyme utilizes a catalytically active site called the SET domain (Suppressor of variegation, Enhancer of Zeste, Trithorax).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The SET domain is a 130-amino acid sequence involved in modulating gene activities.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] This domain has been demonstrated to bind to the histone tail and causes the methylation of the histone.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Differing histone modifications are likely to function in differing ways; acetylation at one position is likely to function differently from acetylation at another position.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Also, multiple modifications may occur at the same time, and these modifications may work together to change the behavior of the nucleosome.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The idea that multiple dynamic modifications regulate gene transcription in a systematic and reproducible way is called the histone code, although the idea that histone state can be read linearly as a digital information carrier has been largely debunked.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] One of the best-understood systems that orchestrate chromatin-based silencing is the SIR protein based silencing of the yeast hidden mating-type loci HML and HMR.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Epigenetic changes of this type thus have the potential to direct increased frequencies of permanent genetic mutation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] DNA methylation patterns are known to be established and modified in response to environmental factors by a complex interplay of at least three independent DNA methyltransferases, DNMT1, DNMT3A, and DNMT3B, the loss of any of which is lethal in mice.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] DNMT1 is the most abundant methyltransferase in somatic cells, localizes to replication foci, has a 10–40-fold preference for hemimethylated DNA and interacts with the proliferating cell nuclear antigen (PCNA).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] By preferentially modifying hemimethylated DNA, DNMT1 transfers patterns of methylation to a newly synthesized strand after DNA replication, and therefore is often referred to as the 'maintenance' methyltransferase.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] DNMT1 is essential for proper embryonic development, imprinting and X-inactivation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] To emphasize the difference of this molecular mechanism of inheritance from the canonical Watson-Crick base-pairing mechanism of transmission of genetic information, the term 'Epigenetic templating' was introduced.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Furthermore, in addition to the maintenance and transmission of methylated DNA states, the same principle could work in the maintenance and transmission of histone modifications and even cytoplasmic (structural) heritable states.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] RNA methylation of N6-methyladenosine (m6A) as the most abundant eukaryotic RNA modification has recently been recognized as an important gene regulatory mechanism.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In 2011, it was demonstrated that the methylation of mRNA plays a critical role in human energy homeostasis.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The obesity-associated FTO gene is shown to be able to demethylate N6-methyladenosine in RNA.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Histones H3 and H4 can also be manipulated through demethylation using histone lysine demethylase (KDM).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] This recently identified enzyme has a catalytically active site called the Jumonji domain (JmjC).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The demethylation occurs when JmjC utilizes multiple cofactors to hydroxylate the methyl group, thereby removing it.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] JmjC is capable of demethylating mono-, di-, and tri-methylated substrates.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Chromosomal regions can adopt stable and heritable alternative states resulting in bistable gene expression without changes to the DNA sequence.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Epigenetic control is often associated with alternative covalent modifications of histones.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The stability and heritability of states of larger chromosomal regions are suggested to involve positive feedback where modified nucleosomes recruit enzymes that similarly modify nearby nucleosomes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] A simplified stochastic model for this type of epigenetics is found here.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] It has been suggested that chromatin-based transcriptional regulation could be mediated by the effect of small RNAs.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Small interfering RNAs can modulate transcriptional gene expression via epigenetic modulation of targeted promoters.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Sometimes, a gene, once activated, transcribes a product that directly or indirectly sustains its own activity.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] For example, Hnf4 and MyoD enhance the transcription of many liver-specific and muscle-specific genes, respectively, including their own, through the transcription factor activity of the proteins they encode.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] RNA signalling includes differential recruitment of a hierarchy of generic chromatin modifying complexes and DNA methyltransferases to specific loci by RNAs during differentiation and development.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Other epigenetic changes are mediated by the production of different splice forms of RNA, or by formation of double-stranded RNA (RNAi).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Descendants of the cell in which the gene was turned on will inherit this activity, even if the original stimulus for gene-activation is no longer present.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] These genes are often turned on or off by signal transduction, although in some systems where syncytia or gap junctions are important, RNA may spread directly to other cells or nuclei by diffusion.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] A large amount of RNA and protein is contributed to the zygote by the mother during oogenesis or via nurse cells, resulting in maternal effect phenotypes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] A smaller quantity of sperm RNA is transmitted from the father, but there is recent evidence that this epigenetic information can lead to visible changes in several generations of offspring.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] MicroRNAs (miRNAs) are members of non-coding RNAs that range in size from 17 to 25 nucleotides. miRNAs regulate a large variety of biological functions in plants and animals.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] So far, in 2013, about 2000 miRNAs have been discovered in humans and these can be found online in a miRNA database.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Each miRNA expressed in a cell may target about 100 to 200 messenger RNAs(mRNAs) that it downregulates.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Most of the downregulation of mRNAs occurs by causing the decay of the targeted mRNA, while some downregulation occurs at the level of translation into protein.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] It appears that about 60% of human protein coding genes are regulated by miRNAs.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Many miRNAs are epigenetically regulated.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] About 50% of miRNA genes are associated with CpG islands, that may be repressed by epigenetic methylation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Transcription from methylated CpG islands is strongly and heritably repressed.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Other miRNAs are epigenetically regulated by either histone modifications or by combined DNA methylation and histone modification.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] sRNAs are small (50–250 nucleotides), highly structured, non-coding RNA fragments found in bacteria.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] They control gene expression including virulence genes in pathogens and are viewed as new targets in the fight against drug-resistant bacteria.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] They play an important role in many biological processes, binding to mRNA and protein targets in prokaryotes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Their phylogenetic analyses, for example through sRNA–mRNA target interactions or protein binding properties, are used to build comprehensive databases. sRNA-gene maps based on their targets in microbial genomes are also constructed.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Numerous investigations have demonstrated the pivotal involvement of long non-coding RNAs (lncRNAs) in the regulation of gene expression and chromosomal modifications, thereby exerting significant control over cellular differentiation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] These long non-coding RNAs also contribute to genomic imprinting and the inactivation of the X chromosome.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In invertebrates such as social insects of honey bees, long non-coding RNAs are detected as a possible epigenetic mechanism via allele-specific genes underlying aggression via reciprocal crosses.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Prions are infectious forms of proteins.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In general, proteins fold into discrete units that perform distinct cellular functions, but some proteins are also capable of forming an infectious conformational state known as a prion.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Although often viewed in the context of infectious disease, prions are more loosely defined by their ability to catalytically convert other native state versions of the same protein to an infectious conformational state.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] It is in this latter sense that they can be viewed as epigenetic agents capable of inducing a phenotypic change without a modification of the genome.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Fungal prions are considered by some to be epigenetic because the infectious phenotype caused by the prion can be inherited without modification of the genome.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] PSI+ and URE3, discovered in yeast in 1965 and 1971, are the two best studied of this type of prion.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Prions can have a phenotypic effect through the sequestration of protein in aggregates, thereby reducing that protein's activity.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In PSI+ cells, the loss of the Sup35 protein (which is involved in termination of translation) causes ribosomes to have a higher rate of read-through of stop codons, an effect that results in suppression of nonsense mutations in other genes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The ability of Sup35 to form prions may be a conserved trait.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] It could confer an adaptive advantage by giving cells the ability to switch into a PSI+ state and express dormant genetic features normally terminated by stop codon mutations.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Prion-based epigenetics has also been observed in *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Epigenetic changes modify the activation of certain genes, but not the genetic code sequence of DNA.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The microstructure (not code) of DNA itself or the associated chromatin proteins may be modified, causing activation or silencing.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] This mechanism enables differentiated cells in a multicellular organism to express only the genes that are necessary for their own activity.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Epigenetic changes are preserved when cells divide.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Most epigenetic changes only occur within the course of one individual organism's lifetime; however, these epigenetic changes can be transmitted to the organism's offspring through a process called transgenerational epigenetic inheritance.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Moreover, if gene inactivation occurs in a sperm or egg cell that results in fertilization, this epigenetic modification may also be transferred to the next generation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] DNA damage can also cause epigenetic changes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] DNA damage is very frequent, occurring on average about 60,000 times a day per cell of the human body (see DNA damage (naturally occurring)).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] These damages are largely repaired, however, epigenetic changes can still remain at the site of DNA repair.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In particular, a double strand break in DNA can initiate unprogrammed epigenetic gene silencing both by causing DNA methylation as well as by promoting silencing types of histone modifications (chromatin remodeling - see next section).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In addition, the enzyme Parp1 (poly(ADP)-ribose polymerase) and its product poly(ADP)-ribose (PAR) accumulate at sites of DNA damage as part of the repair process.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] This accumulation, in turn, directs recruitment and activation of the chromatin remodeling protein, ALC1, that can cause nucleosome remodeling.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Nucleosome remodeling has been found to cause, for instance, epigenetic silencing of DNA repair gene MLH1.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] DNA damaging chemicals, such as benzene, hydroquinone, styrene, carbon tetrachloride and trichloroethylene, cause considerable hypomethylation of DNA, some through the activation of oxidative stress pathways.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Foods are known to alter the epigenetics of rats on different diets.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Some food components epigenetically increase the levels of DNA repair enzymes such as MGMT and MLH1 and p53.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Other food components can reduce DNA damage, such as soy isoflavones.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In one study, markers for oxidative stress, such as modified nucleotides that can result from DNA damage, were decreased by a 3-week diet supplemented with soy.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] A decrease in oxidative DNA damage was also observed 2 h after consumption of anthocyanin-rich bilberry (*Vaccinium myrtillius* L.) pomace extract.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Damage to DNA is very common and is constantly being repaired.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Epigenetic alterations can accompany DNA repair of oxidative damage or double-strand breaks.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In human cells, oxidative DNA damage occurs about 10,000 times a day and DNA double-strand breaks occur about 10 to 50 times a cell cycle in somatic replicating cells (see DNA damage (naturally occurring)).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The selective advantage of DNA repair is to allow the cell to survive in the face of DNA damage.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The selective advantage of epigenetic alterations that occur with DNA repair is not clear.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In the steady state (with endogenous damages occurring and being repaired), there are about 2,400 oxidatively damaged guanines that form 8-oxo-2'-deoxyguanosine (8-OHdG) in the average mammalian cell DNA.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] 8-OHdG constitutes about 5% of the oxidative damages commonly present in DNA.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The oxidized guanines do not occur randomly among all guanines in DNA.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] There is a sequence preference for the guanine at a methylated CpG site (a cytosine followed by guanine along its 5' → 3' direction and where the cytosine is methylated (5-mCpG)).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] A 5-mCpG site has the lowest ionization potential for guanine oxidation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Oxidized guanine has mispairing potential and is mutagenic.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Oxoguanine glycosylase (OGG1) is the primary enzyme responsible for the excision of the oxidized guanine during DNA repair.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] OGG1 finds and binds to an 8-OHdG within a few seconds.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] However, OGG1 does not immediately excise 8-OHdG.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In HeLa cells half maximum removal of 8-OHdG occurs in 30 minutes, and in irradiated mice, the 8-OHdGs induced in the mouse liver are removed with a half-life of 11 minutes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] When OGG1 is present at an oxidized guanine within a methylated CpG site it recruits TET1 to the 8-OHdG lesion (see Figure).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] This allows TET1 to demethylate an adjacent methylated cytosine.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Demethylation of cytosine is an epigenetic alteration.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] As an example, when human mammary epithelial cells were treated with H2O2 for six hours, 8-OHdG increased about 3.5-fold in DNA and this caused about 80% demethylation of the 5-methylcytosines in the genome.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Demethylation of CpGs in a gene promoter by TET enzyme activity increases transcription of the gene into messenger RNA.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In cells treated with H2O2, one particular gene was examined, *BACE1*.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The methylation level of the *BACE1* CpG island was reduced (an epigenetic alteration) and this allowed about 6.5 fold increase of expression of *BACE1* messenger RNA.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] While six-hour incubation with H2O2 causes considerable demethylation of 5-mCpG sites, shorter times of H2O2 incubation appear to promote other epigenetic alterations.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Treatment of cells with H2O2 for 30 minutes causes the mismatch repair protein heterodimer MSH2-MSH6 to recruit DNA methyltransferase 1 (DNMT1) to sites of some kinds of oxidative DNA damage.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] This could cause increased methylation of cytosines (epigenetic alterations) at these locations.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Jiang et al. treated HEK 293 cells with agents causing oxidative DNA damage, (potassium bromate (KBrO3) or potassium chromate (K2CrO4)).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Base excision repair (BER) of oxidative damage occurred with the DNA repair enzyme polymerase beta localizing to oxidized guanines.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Polymerase beta is the main human polymerase in short-patch BER of oxidative DNA damage.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Jiang et al. also found that polymerase beta recruited the DNA methyltransferase protein DNMT3b to BER repair sites.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] They then evaluated the methylation pattern at the single nucleotide level in a small region of DNA including the promoter region and the early transcription region of the BRCA1 gene.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Oxidative DNA damage from bromate modulated the DNA methylation pattern (caused epigenetic alterations) at CpG sites within the region of DNA studied.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In untreated cells, CpGs located at −189, −134, −29, −19, +16, and +19 of the BRCA1 gene had methylated cytosines (where numbering is from the messenger RNA transcription start site, and negative numbers indicate nucleotides in the upstream promoter region).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Bromate treatment-induced oxidation resulted in the loss of cytosine methylation at −189, −134, +16 and +19 while also leading to the formation of new methylation at the CpGs located at −80, −55, −21 and +8 after DNA repair was allowed.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Several articles report the recruitment of DNA methyltransferase 1 (DNMT1) to sites of DNA double-strand breaks.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] During homologous recombinational repair (HR) of the double-strand break, the involvement of DNMT1 causes the two repaired strands of DNA to have different levels of methylated cytosines.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] One strand becomes frequently methylated at about 21 CpG sites downstream of the repaired double-strand break.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The other DNA strand loses methylation at about six CpG sites that were previously methylated downstream of the double-strand break, as well as losing methylation at about five CpG sites that were previously methylated upstream of the double-strand break.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] When the chromosome is replicated, this gives rise to one daughter chromosome that is heavily methylated downstream of the previous break site and one that is unmethylated in the region both upstream and downstream of the previous break site.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] With respect to the gene that was broken by the double-strand break, half of the progeny cells express that gene at a high level and in the other half of the progeny cells expression of that gene is repressed.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] When clones of these cells were maintained for three years, the new methylation patterns were maintained over that time period.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In mice with a CRISPR-mediated homology-directed recombination insertion in their genome there were a large number of increased methylations of CpG sites within the double-strand break-associated insertion.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The frequency of epigenetic alterations causing repression of a gene after an NHEJ repair of a DNA double-strand break in that gene may be about 0.9%.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] In ciliates such as *Tetrahymena* and *Paramecium*, genetically identical cells show heritable differences in the patterns of ciliary rows on their cell surface.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Experimentally altered patterns can be transmitted to daughter cells.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] It seems existing structures act as templates for new structures.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The mechanisms of such inheritance are unclear, but reasons exist to assume that multicellular organisms also use existing cell structures to assemble new ones.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Eukaryotic genomes have numerous nucleosomes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Nucleosome position is not random, and determine the accessibility of DNA to regulatory proteins.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Promoters active in different tissues have been shown to have different nucleosome positioning features.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] This determines differences in gene expression and cell differentiation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] It has been shown that at least some nucleosomes are retained in sperm cells (where most but not all histones are replaced by protamines).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Thus nucleosome positioning is to some degree inheritable.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Recent studies have uncovered connections between nucleosome positioning and other epigenetic factors, such as DNA methylation and hydroxymethylation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Different histone variants are incorporated into specific regions of the genome non-randomly.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] Their differential biochemical characteristics can affect genome functions via their roles in gene regulation, and maintenance of chromosome structures.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p01] The three-dimensional configuration of the genome (the 3D genome) is complex, dynamic and crucial for regulating genomic function and nuclear processes such as DNA replication, transcription and DNA-damage repair.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Memory formation and maintenance are due to epigenetic alterations that cause the required dynamic changes in gene transcription that create and renew memory in neurons.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] An event can set off a chain of reactions that result in altered methylations of a large set of genes in neurons, which give a representation of the event, a memory.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Areas of the brain important in the formation of memories include the hippocampus, medial prefrontal cortex (mPFC), anterior cingulate cortex and amygdala, as shown in the diagram of the human brain in this section.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] When a strong memory is created, as in a rat subjected to contextual fear conditioning (CFC), one of the earliest events to occur is that more than 100 DNA double-strand breaks are formed by topoisomerase IIB in neurons of the hippocampus and the medial prefrontal cortex (mPFC).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] These double-strand breaks are at specific locations that allow activation of transcription of immediate early genes (IEGs) that are important in memory formation, allowing their expression in mRNA, with peak mRNA transcription at seven to ten minutes after CFC.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Two important IEGs in memory formation are *EGR1* and the alternative promoter variant of *DNMT3A*, *DNMT3A2*.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] EGR1 protein binds to DNA at its binding motifs, 5′-GCGTGGGCG-3′ or 5′-GCGGGGGCGG-3', and there are about 12,000 genome locations at which EGR1 protein can bind.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] EGR1 protein binds to DNA in gene promoter and enhancer regions.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] EGR1 recruits the demethylating enzyme TET1 to an association, and brings TET1 to about 600 locations on the genome where TET1 can then demethylate and activate the associated genes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] The DNA methyltransferases DNMT3A1, DNMT3A2 and DNMT3B can all methylate cytosines (see image this section) at CpG sites in or near the promoters of genes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] As shown by Manzo et al., these three DNA methyltransferases differ in their genomic binding locations and DNA methylation activity at different regulatory sites.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Manzo et al. located 3,970 genome regions exclusively enriched for DNMT3A1, 3,838 regions for DNMT3A2 and 3,432 regions for DNMT3B.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] When DNMT3A2 is newly induced as an IEG (when neurons are activated), many new cytosine methylations occur, presumably in the target regions of DNMT3A2.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Oliviera et al. found that the neuronal activity-inducible IEG levels of Dnmt3a2 in the hippocampus determined the ability to form long-term memories.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Rats form long-term associative memories after contextual fear conditioning.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Duke et al. found that 24 hours after CFC in rats, in hippocampus neurons, 2,097 genes (9.17% of the genes in the rat genome) had altered methylation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] When newly methylated cytosines are present in CpG sites in the promoter regions of genes, the genes are often repressed, and when newly demethylated cytosines are present the genes may be activated.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] After CFC, there were 1,048 genes with reduced mRNA expression and 564 genes with upregulated mRNA expression.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Similarly, when mice undergo CFC, one hour later in the hippocampus region of the mouse brain there are 675 demethylated genes and 613 hypermethylated genes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] However, memories do not remain in the hippocampus, but after four or five weeks the memories are stored in the anterior cingulate cortex.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] The epigenetic alteration of methylation after a new memory is established creates a different pool of nuclear mRNAs.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] As reviewed by Bernstein, the epigenetically determined new mix of nuclear mRNAs are often packaged into neuronal granules, or messenger RNP, consisting of mRNA, small and large ribosomal subunits, translation initiation factors and RNA-binding proteins that regulate mRNA function.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] These neuronal granules are transported from the neuron nucleus and are directed, according to 3′ untranslated regions of the mRNA in the granules (their "zip codes"), to neuronal dendrites.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Roughly 2,500 mRNAs may be localized to the dendrites of hippocampal pyramidal neurons and perhaps 450 transcripts are in excitatory presynaptic nerve terminals (dendritic spines).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] The altered assortments of transcripts (dependent on epigenetic alterations in the neuron nucleus) have different sensitivities in response to signals, which is the basis of altered synaptic plasticity.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Altered synaptic plasticity is often considered the neurochemical foundation of learning and memory.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Epigenetics play a major role in brain aging and age-related cognitive decline, with relevance to life extension.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] In adulthood, changes in the epigenome are important for various higher cognitive functions.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Dysregulation of epigenetic mechanisms is implicated in neurodegenerative disorders and diseases.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Epigenetic modifications in neurons are dynamic and reversible.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Epigenetic regulation impacts neuronal action, affecting learning, memory, and other cognitive processes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Early events, including during embryonic development, can influence development, cognition, and health outcomes through epigenetic mechanisms.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Epigenetic mechanisms have been proposed as "a potential molecular mechanism for effects of endogenous hormones on the organization of developing brain circuits".
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Nutrients could interact with the epigenome to "protect or boost cognitive processes across the lifespan".
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] A review suggests neurobiological effects of physical exercise via epigenetics seem "central to building an 'epigenetic memory' to influence long-term brain function and behavior" and may even be heritable.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] With the axo-ciliary synapse, there is communication between serotonergic axons and antenna-like primary cilia of CA1 pyramidal neurons that alters the neuron's epigenetic state in the nucleus via the signalling distinct from that at the plasma membrane (and longer-term).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Epigenetics also play a major role in the brain evolution in and to humans.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Developmental epigenetics can be divided into predetermined and probabilistic epigenesis.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Predetermined epigenesis is a unidirectional movement from structural development in DNA to the functional maturation of the protein.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] "Predetermined" here means that development is scripted and predictable.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Probabilistic epigenesis on the other hand is a bidirectional structure-function development with experiences and external molding development.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Somatic epigenetic inheritance, particularly through DNA and histone covalent modifications and nucleosome repositioning, is very important in the development of multicellular eukaryotic organisms.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] The genome sequence is static (with some notable exceptions), but cells differentiate into many different types, which perform different functions, and respond differently to the environment and intercellular signaling.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Thus, as individuals develop, morphogens activate or silence genes in an epigenetically heritable fashion, giving cells a memory.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] In mammals, most cells terminally differentiate, with only stem cells retaining the ability to differentiate into several cell types ("totipotency" and "multipotency").
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] In mammals, some stem cells continue producing newly differentiated cells throughout life, such as in neurogenesis, but mammals are not able to respond to loss of some tissues, for example, the inability to regenerate limbs, which some other animals are capable of.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Epigenetic modifications regulate the transition from neural stem cells to glial progenitor cells (for example, differentiation into oligodendrocytes is regulated by the deacetylation and methylation of histones).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Unlike animals, plant cells do not terminally differentiate, remaining totipotent with the ability to give rise to a new individual plant.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Epigenetic changes can occur in response to environmental exposure – for example, maternal dietary supplementation with genistein (250 mg/kg) have epigenetic changes affecting expression of the agouti gene, which affects their fur color, weight, and propensity to develop cancer.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Ongoing research is focused on exploring the impact of other known teratogens, such as diabetic embryopathy, on methylation signatures.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Controversial results from one study suggested that traumatic experiences might produce an epigenetic signal that is capable of being passed to future generations.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Mice were trained, using foot shocks, to fear a cherry blossom odor.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] The investigators reported that the mouse offspring had an increased aversion to this specific odor.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] They suggested epigenetic changes that increase gene expression, rather than in DNA itself, in a gene, M71, that governs the functioning of an odor receptor in the nose that responds specifically to this cherry blossom smell.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] There were physical changes that correlated with olfactory (smell) function in the brains of the trained mice and their descendants.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Several criticisms were reported, including the study's low statistical power as evidence of some irregularity such as bias in reporting results.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Due to limits of sample size, there is a probability that an effect will not be demonstrated to within statistical significance even if it exists.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] The criticism suggested that the probability that all the experiments reported would show positive results if an identical protocol was followed, assuming the claimed effects exist, is merely 0.4%.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] The authors also did not indicate which mice were siblings, and treated all of the mice as statistically independent.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] The original researchers pointed out negative results in the paper's appendix that the criticism omitted in its calculations, and undertook to track which mice were siblings in the future.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Epigenetic mechanisms were a necessary part of the evolutionary origin of cell differentiation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Although most of these multigenerational epigenetic traits are gradually lost over several generations, the possibility remains that multigenerational epigenetics could be another aspect to evolution and adaptation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] As mentioned above, some define epigenetics as heritable.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] A sequestered germ line or Weismann barrier is specific to animals, and epigenetic inheritance is more common in plants and microbes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Lamb and Étienne Danchin have argued that these effects may require enhancements to the standard conceptual framework of the modern synthesis and have called for an extended evolutionary synthesis.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Other evolutionary biologists, such as John Maynard Smith, have incorporated epigenetic inheritance into population-genetics models or are openly skeptical of the extended evolutionary synthesis (Michael Lynch).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Thomas Dickins and Qazi Rahman state that epigenetic mechanisms such as DNA methylation and histone modification are genetically inherited under the control of natural selection and therefore fit under the earlier "modern synthesis".
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] In plants, heritable DNA methylation mutations are 100,000 times more likely to occur compared to DNA mutations.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] An epigenetically inherited element such as the PSI+ system can act as a "stop-gap", good enough for short-term adaptation that allows the lineage to survive for long enough for mutation and/or recombination to genetically assimilate the adaptive phenotypic change.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] The existence of this possibility increases the evolvability of a species.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] More than 100 cases of transgenerational epigenetic inheritance phenomena have been reported in a wide range of organisms, including prokaryotes, plants, and animals.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] For instance, mourning-cloak butterflies will change color through hormone changes in response to experimentation of varying temperatures.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] The filamentous fungus *Neurospora crassa* is a prominent model system for understanding the control and function of cytosine methylation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] In this organism, DNA methylation is associated with relics of a genome-defense system called RIP (repeat-induced point mutation) and silences gene expression by inhibiting transcription elongation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] The yeast prion PSI is generated by a conformational change of a translation termination factor, which is then inherited by daughter cells.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] This can provide a survival advantage under adverse conditions, exemplifying epigenetic regulation which enables unicellular organisms to respond rapidly to environmental stress.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Prions can be viewed as epigenetic agents capable of inducing a phenotypic change without modification of the genome.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Direct detection of epigenetic marks in microorganisms is possible with single molecule real time sequencing, in which polymerase sensitivity allows for measuring methylation and other modifications as a DNA molecule is being sequenced.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Several projects have demonstrated the ability to collect genome-wide epigenetic data in bacteria.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] While epigenetics is of fundamental importance in eukaryotes, especially metazoans, it plays a different role in bacteria.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Most importantly, eukaryotes use epigenetic mechanisms primarily to regulate gene expression which bacteria rarely do.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] However, bacteria make widespread use of postreplicative DNA methylation for the epigenetic control of DNA-protein interactions.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Bacteria also use DNA adenine methylation (rather than DNA cytosine methylation) as an epigenetic signal.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] DNA adenine methylation is important in bacteria virulence in organisms such as *Escherichia coli*, *Salmonella, Vibrio, Yersinia, Haemophilus*, and *Brucella*.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] In *Alphaproteobacteria*, methylation of adenine regulates the cell cycle and couples gene transcription to DNA replication.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] In *Gammaproteobacteria*, adenine methylation provides signals for DNA replication, chromosome segregation, mismatch repair, packaging of bacteriophage, transposase activity and regulation of gene expression.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] There exists a genetic switch controlling *Streptococcus pneumoniae* (the pneumococcus) that allows the bacterium to randomly change its characteristics into six alternative states that could pave the way to improved vaccines.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Each form is randomly generated by a phase variable methylation system.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] The ability of the pneumococcus to cause deadly infections is different in each of these six states.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Similar systems exist in other bacterial genera.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] In Bacillota such as *Clostridioides difficile,* adenine methylation regulates sporulation, biofilm formation and host-adaptation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Epigenetics has many and varied potential medical applications.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Direct comparisons of identical twins constitute an optimal model for interrogating environmental epigenetics.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] In the case of humans with different environmental exposures, monozygotic (identical) twins were epigenetically indistinguishable during their early years, while older twins had remarkable differences in the overall content and genomic distribution of 5-methylcytosine DNA and histone acetylation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] The twin pairs who had spent less of their lifetime together and/or had greater differences in their medical histories were those who showed the largest differences in their levels of 5-methylcytosine DNA and acetylation of histones H3 and H4.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Dizygotic (fraternal) and monozygotic (identical) twins show evidence of epigenetic influence in humans.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] DNA sequence differences that would be abundant in a singleton-based study do not interfere with the analysis.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Environmental differences can produce long-term epigenetic effects, and different developmental monozygotic twin subtypes may be different with respect to their susceptibility to be discordant from an epigenetic point of view.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] A high-throughput study, which denotes technology that looks at extensive genetic markers, focused on epigenetic differences between monozygotic twins to compare global and locus-specific changes in DNA methylation and histone modifications in a sample of 40 monozygotic twin pairs.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] In this case, only healthy twin pairs were studied, but a wide range of ages was represented, between 3 and 74 years.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] One of the major conclusions from this study was that there is an age-dependent accumulation of epigenetic differences between the two siblings of twin pairs.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] This accumulation suggests the existence of epigenetic "drift".
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] *Epigenetic drift* is the term given to epigenetic modifications as they occur as a direct function with age.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] While age is a known risk factor for many diseases, age-related methylation has been found to occur differentially at specific sites along the genome.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Over time, this can result in measurable differences between biological and chronological age.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Epigenetic changes have been found to be reflective of lifestyle and may act as functional biomarkers of disease before clinical threshold is reached.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] A more recent study, where 114 monozygotic twins and 80 dizygotic twins were analyzed for the DNA methylation status of around 6000 unique genomic regions, concluded that epigenetic similarity at the time of blastocyst splitting may also contribute to phenotypic similarities in monozygotic co-twins.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] This supports the notion that microenvironment at early stages of embryonic development can be quite important for the establishment of epigenetic marks.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Congenital genetic disease is well understood and it is clear that epigenetics can play a role, for example, in the case of Angelman syndrome and Prader–Willi syndrome.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Some human disorders are associated with genomic imprinting, a phenomenon in mammals where the father and mother contribute different epigenetic patterns for specific genomic loci in their germ cells.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] In the Överkalix study, paternal (but not maternal) grandsons of Swedish men who were exposed during preadolescence to famine in the 19th century were less likely to die of cardiovascular disease.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] If food was plentiful, then diabetes mortality in the grandchildren increased, suggesting that this was a transgenerational epigenetic inheritance.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] The opposite effect was observed for females – the paternal (but not maternal) granddaughters of women who experienced famine while in the womb (and therefore while their eggs were being formed) lived shorter lives on average.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] The use of beta-lactam antibiotics can alter glutamate receptor activity and the action of cyclosporine on multiple transcription factors.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Additionally, lithium can impact autophagy of aberrant proteins, and opioid drugs via chronic use can increase the expression of genes associated with addictive phenotypes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] However, whether and to what extent epigenetic effects can be transmitted across generations remains unclear, particularly in humans.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Addiction is a disorder of the brain's reward system which arises through transcriptional and neuroepigenetic mechanisms and occurs over time from chronically high levels of exposure to an addictive stimulus (e.g., morphine, cocaine, sexual intercourse, gambling).
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Transgenerational epigenetic inheritance of addictive phenotypes has been noted to occur in preclinical studies.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] However, robust evidence in support of the persistence of epigenetic effects across multiple generations has yet to be established in humans; for example, an epigenetic effect of prenatal exposure to smoking that is observed in great-grandchildren who had not been exposed.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Studies indicate that epigenetics can also play a role in cancer, specifically epigenetic abnormalities and the initiation and progression of cancer.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Cancer is considered both genetic and an epigenetic disease.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] This includes components such as DNA methylation, histone modifications, and microRNA expression, which can lead to malignant cell growth.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] The two forms of heritable information, namely genetic and epigenetic, are collectively called dual inheritance.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Members of the APOBEC/AID family of cytosine deaminases may concurrently influence genetic and epigenetic inheritance using similar molecular mechanisms, and may be a point of crosstalk between these conceptually compartmentalized processes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Fluoroquinolone antibiotics induce epigenetic changes in mammalian cells through iron chelation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] This leads to epigenetic effects through inhibition of α-ketoglutarate-dependent dioxygenases that require iron as a co-factor.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Various pharmacological agents are applied for the production of induced pluripotent stem cells (iPSC) or maintain the embryonic stem cell (ESC) phenotypic via epigenetic approach.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Adult stem cells like bone marrow stem cells have also shown a potential to differentiate into cardiac competent cells when treated with G9a histone methyltransferase inhibitor BIX01294.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Cell plasticity, which is the adaptation of cells to stimuli without changes in their genetic code, requires epigenetic changes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] These have been observed in cell plasticity in cancer cells during epithelial-to-mesenchymal transition and also in immune cells, such as macrophages.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Interestingly, metabolic changes underlie these adaptations, since various metabolites play crucial roles in the chemistry of epigenetic marks.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] This includes for instance alpha-ketoglutarate, which is required for histone demethylation, and acetyl-Coenzyme A, which is required for histone acetylation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Epigenetic regulation of gene expression that could be altered or used in epigenome editing are or include mRNA/lncRNA modification, DNA methylation modification and histone modification.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Methylation is a widely characterized mechanism of genetic regulation that can determine biological traits.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] However, strong experimental evidences correlate methylation patterns in SNPs as an important additional feature for the classical activation/inhibition epigenetic dogma.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Molecular interaction data, supported by colocalization analyses, identify multiple nuclear regulatory pathways, linking sequence variation to disturbances in DNA methylation and molecular and phenotypic variation.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] SNP rs730775 is located in the first intron of *NFKBIE* and is a *cis* eQTL for *NFKBIE* in whole blood.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Nuclear factor (NF)-κB inhibitor ε (NFKBIE) directly inhibits NF-κB1 activity and is significantly co-expressed with NF-κB1, also, it is associated with rheumatoid arthritis.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Colocalization analysis supports that variants for the majority of the CpG sites in SNP rs730775 cause genetic variation at the *NFKBIE* locus which is suggestible linked to rheumatoid arthritis through *trans* acting regulation of DNA methylation by NF-κB.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Fatty acid desaturase 1 (FADS1) is a key enzyme in the metabolism of fatty acids.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Moreover, rs174548 in the *FADS1* gene shows increased correlation with DNA methylation in people with high abundance of CD8+ T cells.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] SNP rs174548 is strongly associated with concentrations of arachidonic acid and other metabolites in fatty acid metabolism, blood eosinophil counts. and inflammatory diseases such as asthma.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Interaction results indicated a correlation between rs174548 and asthma, providing new insights about fatty acid metabolism in CD8+ T cells with immune phenotypes.
[src:epigenetics/epigenetics-p02] Misuse of the scientific term by quack authors has produced misinformation among the general public.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Genomic imprinting is an inheritance process independent of the classical Mendelian inheritance.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] It is an epigenetic process that involves DNA methylation and histone methylation without altering the genetic sequence.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] These epigenetic marks are established ("imprinted") in the germline (sperm or egg cells) of the parents and are maintained through mitotic cell divisions in the somatic cells of an organism.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Appropriate imprinting of certain genes is important for normal development.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Human diseases involving genomic imprinting include Angelman, Prader–Willi, and Beckwith–Wiedemann syndromes.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Methylation defects have also been associated with male infertility.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] In diploid organisms (like humans), the somatic cells possess two copies of the genome, one inherited from the male and one from the female.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Each autosomal gene is therefore represented by two copies, or alleles, with one copy inherited from each parent at fertilization.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The expressed allele is dependent upon its parental origin.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] For example, the gene encoding insulin-like growth factor 2 (IGF2/Igf2) is only expressed from the allele inherited from the male.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Although imprinting accounts for a small proportion of mammalian genes, they play an important role in embryogenesis particularly in the formation of visceral structures and the nervous system.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The term "imprinting" was first used to describe events in the insect *Pseudococcus nipae*.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] In Pseudococcids (mealybugs) (Hemiptera, Coccoidea) both the male and female develop from a fertilised egg.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] In females, all chromosomes remain euchromatic and functional.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] In embryos destined to become males, one haploid set of chromosomes becomes heterochromatinised after the sixth cleavage division and remains so in most tissues; males are thus functionally haploid.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] That imprinting might be a feature of mammalian development was suggested in breeding experiments in mice carrying reciprocal chromosomal translocations.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Nucleus transplantation experiments in mouse zygotes in the early 1980s confirmed that normal development requires the contribution of both the maternal and paternal genomes.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The vast majority of mouse embryos derived from parthenogenesis (called parthenogenones, with two maternal or egg genomes) and androgenesis (called androgenones, with two paternal or sperm genomes) die at or before the blastocyst/implantation stage.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] In the rare instances that they develop to postimplantation stages, gynogenetic embryos show better embryonic development relative to placental development, while for androgenones, the reverse is true.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Nevertheless, for the latter, only a few have been described (in a 1984 paper).
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Nevertheless, in 2018 genome editing allowed for bipaternal and viable bimaternal mouse and even (in 2022) parthenogenesis, still this is far from full reimprinting.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Finally in March 2023 viable bipaternal embryos were created.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] No naturally occurring cases of parthenogenesis exist in mammals because of imprinted genes.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The researchers were able to succeed by using one egg from an immature parent, thus reducing maternal imprinting, and modifying it to express the gene Igf2, which is normally only expressed by the paternal copy of the gene.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Parthenogenetic/gynogenetic embryos have twice the normal expression level of maternally derived genes, and lack expression of paternally expressed genes, while the reverse is true for androgenetic embryos.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] It is now known that there are at least 80 imprinted genes in humans and mice, many of which are involved in embryonic and placental growth and development.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Hybrid offspring of two species may exhibit unusual growth due to the novel combination of imprinted genes.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Various methods have been used to identify imprinted genes.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] In swine, Bischoff *et al.* compared transcriptional profiles using DNA microarrays to survey differentially expressed genes between parthenotes (2 maternal genomes) and control fetuses (1 maternal, 1 paternal genome).
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] An intriguing study surveying the transcriptome of murine brain tissues revealed over 1300 imprinted gene loci (approximately 10-fold more than previously reported) by RNA-sequencing from F1 hybrids resulting from reciprocal crosses.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The result however has been challenged by others who claimed that this is an overestimation by an order of magnitude due to flawed statistical analysis.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] In domesticated livestock, single-nucleotide polymorphisms in imprinted genes influencing foetal growth and development have been shown to be associated with economically important production traits in cattle, sheep and pigs.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] At the same time as the generation of the gynogenetic and androgenetic embryos discussed above, mouse embryos were also being generated that contained only small regions that were derived from either a paternal or maternal source.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The generation of a series of such uniparental disomies, which together span the entire genome, allowed the creation of an imprinting map.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Those regions which when inherited from a single parent result in a discernible phenotype contain imprinted gene(s).
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Further research showed that within these regions there were often numerous imprinted genes.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Around 80% of imprinted genes are found in clusters such as these, called imprinted domains, suggesting a level of co-ordinated control.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] It must be possible to erase and re-establish imprints through each generation so that genes that are imprinted in an adult may still be expressed in that adult's offspring.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] (For example, the maternal genes that control insulin production will be imprinted in a male but will be expressed in any of the male's offspring that inherit these genes.) The nature of imprinting must therefore be epigenetic rather than DNA sequence dependent.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] In germline cells the imprint is erased and then re-established according to the sex of the individual, i.e. in the developing sperm (during spermatogenesis), a paternal imprint is established, whereas in developing oocytes (oogenesis), a maternal imprint is established.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] This process of erasure and reprogramming is necessary such that the germ cell imprinting status is relevant to the sex of the individual.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] In both plants and mammals there are two major mechanisms that are involved in establishing the imprint; these are DNA methylation and histone modifications.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Recently, a new study has suggested a novel inheritable imprinting mechanism in humans that would be specific of placental tissue and that is independent of DNA methylation (the main and classical mechanism for genomic imprinting).
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] This was observed in humans, but not in mice, suggesting development after the evolutionary divergence of humans and mice, ~80 Mya.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The grouping of imprinted genes within clusters allows them to share common regulatory elements, such as non-coding RNAs and differentially methylated regions (DMRs).
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] When these regulatory elements control the imprinting of one or more genes, they are known as imprinting control regions (ICR).
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The expression of non-coding RNAs, such as antisense Igf2r RNA (*Air*) on mouse chromosome 17 and KCNQ1OT1 on human chromosome 11p15.5, have been shown to be essential for the imprinting of genes in their corresponding regions.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Differentially methylated regions are generally segments of DNA rich in cytosine and guanine nucleotides, with the cytosine nucleotides methylated on one copy but not on the other.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Contrary to expectation, methylation does not necessarily mean silencing; instead, the effect of methylation depends upon the default state of the region.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The control of expression of specific genes by genomic imprinting is unique to therian mammals (placental mammals and marsupials) and flowering plants.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Imprinting of whole chromosomes has been reported in mealybugs (Genus: *Pseudococcus*) and a fungus gnat (*Sciara*).
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] It has also been established that X-chromosome inactivation occurs in an imprinted manner in the extra-embryonic tissues of mice and all tissues in marsupials, where it is always the paternal X-chromosome which is silenced.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The majority of imprinted genes in mammals have been found to have roles in the control of embryonic growth and development, including development of the placenta.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Other imprinted genes are involved in post-natal development, with roles affecting suckling and metabolism.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] A widely accepted hypothesis for the evolution of genomic imprinting is the "parental conflict hypothesis".
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Also known as the kinship theory of genomic imprinting, this hypothesis states that the inequality between parental genomes due to imprinting is a result of the differing interests of each parent in terms of the evolutionary fitness of their genes.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The father's genes that encode for imprinting gain greater fitness through the success of the offspring, at the expense of the mother.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The mother's evolutionary imperative is often to conserve resources for her own survival while providing sufficient nourishment to current and subsequent litters.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Accordingly, paternally expressed genes tend to be growth-promoting whereas maternally expressed genes tend to be growth-limiting.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] A small number of imprinted genes are fast evolving under positive Darwinian selection possibly due to antagonistic co-evolution.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The majority of imprinted genes display high levels of micro-synteny conservation and have undergone very few duplications in placental mammalian lineages.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Another hypothesis proposed is that some imprinted genes act coadaptively to improve both fetal development and maternal provisioning for nutrition and care.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] In it, a subset of paternally expressed genes are co-expressed in both the placenta and the mother's hypothalamus.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] This would come about through selective pressure from parent-infant coadaptation to improve infant survival.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Paternally expressed 3 (*PEG3*) is a gene for which this hypothesis may apply.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Others have approached their study of the origins of genomic imprinting from a different side, arguing that natural selection is operating on the role of epigenetic marks as machinery for homologous chromosome recognition during meiosis, rather than on their role in differential expression.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] This argument centers on the existence of epigenetic effects on chromosomes that do not directly affect gene expression, but do depend on which parent the chromosome originated from.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] This diversity in organisms that show parental origin effects has prompted theorists to place the evolutionary origin of genomic imprinting before the last common ancestor of plants and animals, over a billion years ago.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Natural selection for genomic imprinting requires genetic variation in a population.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] A hypothesis for the origin of this genetic variation states that the host-defense system responsible for silencing foreign DNA elements, such as genes of viral origin, mistakenly silenced genes whose silencing turned out to be beneficial for the organism.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] There appears to be an over-representation of retrotransposed genes, that is to say genes that are inserted into the genome by viruses, among imprinted genes.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] It has also been postulated that if the retrotransposed gene is inserted close to another imprinted gene, it may just acquire this imprint.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Unfortunately, the relationship between the phenotype and genotype of imprinted genes is solely conceptual.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The idea is frameworked using two alleles on a single locus and hosts three different possible classes of genotypes.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The reciprocal heterozygotes genotype class contributes to understanding how imprinting will impact genotype to phenotype relationship.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Reciprocal heterozygotes have a genetically equivalent, but they are phenotypically nonequivalent.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Their phenotype may not be dependent on the equivalence of the genotype.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] This can ultimately increase diversity in genetic classes, expanding flexibility of imprinted genes.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] This increase will also force a higher degree in testing capabilities and assortment of tests to determine the presences of imprinting.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] When a locus is identified as imprinted, two different classes express different alleles.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Inherited imprinted genes of offspring are believed to be monoallelic expressions.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] A single locus will entirely produce one's phenotype although two alleles are inherited.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] This genotype class is called parental imprinting, as well as dominant imprinting.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Phenotypic patterns are variant to possible expressions from paternal and maternal genotypes.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Different alleles inherited from different parents will host different phenotypic qualities.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] One allele will have a larger phenotypic value and the other allele will be silenced.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Underdominance of the locus is another possibility of phenotypic expression.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Both maternal and paternal phenotypes will have a small value rather than one hosting a large value and silencing the other.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Statistical frameworks and mapping models are used to identify imprinting effects on genes and complex traits.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Allelic parent-of-origin influences the vary in phenotype that derive from the imprinting of genotype classes.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] These models of mapping and identifying imprinting effects include using unordered genotypes to build mapping models.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] These models will show classic quantitative genetics and the effects of dominance of the imprinted genes.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Imprinting may cause problems in cloning, with clones having DNA that is not methylated in the correct positions.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] It is possible that this is due to a lack of time for reprogramming to be completely achieved.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] When a nucleus is added to an egg during somatic cell nuclear transfer, the egg starts dividing in minutes, as compared to the days or months it takes for reprogramming during embryonic development.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] If time is the responsible factor, it may be possible to delay cell division in clones, giving time for proper reprogramming to occur.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] In vitro fertilisation, including ICSI, is associated with an increased risk of imprinting disorders, with an odds ratio of 3.7 (95% confidence interval 1.4 to 9.7).
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Epigenetic deregulations at H19 imprinted gene in sperm have been observed associated with male infertility.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Indeed, methylation loss at H19 imprinted gene has been observed associated with MTHFR gene promoter hypermethylation in semen samples from infertile males.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The first imprinted genetic disorders to be described in humans were the reciprocally inherited Prader-Willi syndrome and Angelman syndrome.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Both syndromes are associated with loss of the chromosomal region 15q11-13 (band 11 of the long arm of chromosome 15).
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] This region contains the paternally expressed genes SNRPN and NDN and the maternally expressed gene UBE3A.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The imprinted brain hypothesis is a hypothesis in evolutionary psychology regarding the causes of autism spectrum and schizophrenia spectrum disorders, first presented by Bernard Crespi and Christopher Badcock in 2008.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] It hypothesizes that genomic imprinting effects contribute, to some degree, to the diametric (opposite) nature of autism and psychosis (the diametric disorders hypothesis, which is much more general than the imprinted brain idea).
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The imprinted brain hypothesis is based around genomic imprinting, an epigenetic process through which genes are expressed differently depending upon which parent they are inherited from.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Specifically, the imprinted brain hypothesis proposes that autism spectrum disorders are caused to some degree by biases towards paternal gene expression, while psychosis spectrum disorders are caused in some cases by biases towards maternal gene expression.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The imprinted brain hypothesis is supported by high rates of autism in Angelman syndrome (which is due to paternal imprinted gene biases) and high rates of psychosis in Prader-Willi-syndrome (which is due to maternal imprinted gene biases).
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The diametric disorders hypothesis and the imprinted brain hypothesis have been subject to considerable research and testing, with considerable support and some non-supportive evidence, e.g., .
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] DIRAS3 is a paternally expressed and maternally imprinted gene located on chromosome 1 in humans.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Reduced DIRAS3 expression is linked to an increased risk of ovarian and breast cancers; in 41% of breast and ovarian cancers the protein encoded by DIRAS3 is not expressed, suggesting that it functions as a tumor suppressor gene.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Therefore, if uniparental disomy occurs and a person inherits both chromosomes from the mother, the gene will not be expressed and the individual is put at a greater risk for breast and ovarian cancer.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Other conditions involving imprinting include Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome, Silver-Russell syndrome, and pseudohypoparathyroidism.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Transient neonatal diabetes mellitus can also involve imprinting.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] In insects, imprinting affects entire chromosomes.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] In some insects the entire paternal genome is silenced in male offspring, and thus is involved in sex determination.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The imprinting produces effects similar to the mechanisms in other insects that eliminate paternally inherited chromosomes in male offspring, including arrhenotoky.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] In social honey bees, the parent of origin and allele-specific genes has been studied from reciprocal crosses to explore the epigenetic mechanisms underlying aggressive behavior.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] In placental species, parent-offspring conflict can result in the evolution of strategies, such as genomic imprinting, for embryos to subvert maternal nutrient provisioning.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Despite several attempts to find it, genomic imprinting has not been found in the platypus, reptiles, birds, or fish.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The absence of genomic imprinting in a placental reptile, the Pseudemoia entrecasteauxii, is interesting as genomic imprinting was thought to be associated with the evolution of viviparity and placental nutrient transport.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Studies in domestic livestock, such as dairy and beef cattle, have implicated imprinted genes (e.g.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] IGF2) in a range of economic traits, including dairy performance in Holstein-Friesian cattle.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] In sheep, the CLPG gene ("callipyge" from Greek, meaning "beautiful buttocks") produces a large buttocks consisting of muscle with very little fat.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The large-buttocked phenotype only occurs when the allele is present on the copy of chromosome 18 inherited from a sheep's father and is *not* on the copy of chromosome 18 inherited from that sheep's mother.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The CLPG locus is encompassed by Dlk1-Gtl2, an imprinted region of the mammalian genome, and the atypical presentation of this gene is a result of this imprinting.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Foraging behavior in mice studied is influenced by a sexually dimorphic allele expression implicating a cross-gender imprinting influence that varies throughout the body and may dominate expression and shape a behavior.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] A similar imprinting phenomenon has also been described in flowering plants (angiosperms).
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] During fertilization of the egg cell, a second, separate fertilization event gives rise to the endosperm, an extraembryonic structure that nourishes the embryo in a manner analogous to the mammalian placenta.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Unlike the embryo, the endosperm is often formed from the fusion of two maternal cells with a male gamete.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] The 2:1 ratio of maternal to paternal genomes appears to be critical for seed development.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Some genes are found to be expressed from both maternal genomes while others are expressed exclusively from the lone paternal copy.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] It has been suggested that these imprinted genes are responsible for the triploid block effect in flowering plants that prevents hybridization between diploids and autotetraploids.
[src:epigenetics/genomic-imprinting] Several computational methods to detect imprinting genes in plants from reciprocal crosses have been proposed.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] In biology, **histones** are highly-basic proteins abundant in lysine and arginine residues that are found in eukaryotic cell nuclei and in most Archaeal phyla.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] They act as spools around which DNA winds to create structural units called nucleosomes.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Nucleosomes in turn are wrapped into 30-nanometer fibers that form tightly packed chromatin.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histones prevent DNA from becoming tangled and protect it from DNA damage.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] In addition, histones play important roles in gene regulation and DNA replication.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Without histones, unwound DNA in chromosomes would be very long.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] For example, each human cell has about 1.8 meters of DNA if completely stretched out; however, when wound about histones, this length is reduced to about 9 micrometers (0.009 mm) of 30 nm diameter chromatin fibers.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] There are five families of histones, which are designated H1/H5 (linker histones), H2, H3, and H4 (core histones).
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The nucleosome core is formed of two H2A-H2B dimers and a H3-H4 tetramer.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The tight wrapping of DNA around histones, is to a large degree, a result of electrostatic attraction between the positively charged histones and negatively charged phosphate backbone of DNA.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histones may be chemically modified through the action of enzymes to regulate gene transcription.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The most common modifications are the methylation of arginine or lysine residues or the acetylation of lysine.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Methylation can affect how other proteins such as transcription factors interact with the nucleosomes.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Lysine acetylation eliminates a positive charge on lysine thereby weakening the electrostatic attraction between histone and DNA, resulting in partial unwinding of the DNA, making it more accessible for gene expression.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Five major families of histone proteins exist: H1/H5, H2A, H2B, H3, and H4.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histones H2A, H2B, H3 and H4 are known as the core or nucleosomal histones, while histones H1/H5 are known as the **linker histones**.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The core histones all exist as dimers, which are similar in that they all possess the histone fold domain: three alpha helices linked by two loops.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] It is this helical structure that allows for interaction between distinct dimers, particularly in a head-tail fashion (also called the handshake motif).
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The resulting four distinct dimers then come together to form one octameric nucleosome core, approximately 63 Angstroms in diameter (a solenoid (DNA)-like particle).
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Around 146 base pairs (bp) of DNA wrap around this core particle 1.65 times in a left-handed super-helical turn to give a particle of around 100 Angstroms across.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The linker histone H1 binds the nucleosome at the entry and exit sites of the DNA, thus locking the DNA into place and allowing the formation of higher order structure.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The most basic such formation is the 10 nm fiber or beads on a string conformation.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This involves the wrapping of DNA around nucleosomes with approximately 50 base pairs of DNA separating each pair of nucleosomes (also referred to as linker DNA).
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Higher-order structures include the 30 nm fiber (forming an irregular zigzag) and 100 nm fiber, these being the structures found in normal cells.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] During mitosis and meiosis, the condensed chromosomes are assembled through interactions between nucleosomes and other regulatory proteins.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histones are subdivided into canonical replication-dependent histones, whose genes are expressed during the S-phase of the cell cycle and replication-independent histone variants, expressed during the whole cell cycle.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] In mammals, genes encoding canonical histones are typically clustered along chromosomes in 4 different highly-conserved loci, lack introns and use a stem loop structure at the 3' end instead of a polyA tail.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Genes encoding histone variants are usually not clustered, have introns and their mRNAs are regulated with polyA tails.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Complex multicellular organisms typically have a higher number of histone variants providing a variety of different functions.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Functionally, histone variants contribute to transcriptional control, epigenetic memory, and DNA repair, serving specialized functions beyond nucleosome packaging which plays distinct roles in chromatin dynamics.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] For example, H2A.Z is enriched at regulatory elements and promoters of actively transcribed genes, where it modulates nucleosome stability and transcription factor binding.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] In contrast, H3.3, a replacement variant of Histone H3, is associated with active transcription and is preferentially deposited at enhancer elements and transcribed gene bodies.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Another critical variant, CENPA, replaces H3 in centromeric nucleosomes, providing a structural foundation essential for chromosome segregation.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Variants also play essential roles in DNA repair.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Variants such as H2A.X are phosphorylated at sites of DNA damage, marking regions for recruitment of repair proteins.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This modification, commonly referred to as γH2A.X, serves as a key signal in the cellular response to double-strand breaks, facilitating efficient DNA repair processes.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Defects in histone variant regulation have been linked to genome instability, a hallmark of many cancers and age-related diseases.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Recent data are accumulating about the roles of diverse histone variants highlighting the functional links between variants and the delicate regulation of organism development.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histone variants proteins from different organisms, their classification and variant specific features can be found in "HistoneDB 2.0 - Variants" database.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Several pseudogenes have also been discovered and identified in very close sequences of their respective functional ortholog genes.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The nucleosome core is formed of two H2A-H2B dimers and a H3-H4 tetramer, forming two nearly symmetrical halves by tertiary structure (C2 symmetry; one macromolecule is the mirror image of the other).
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The H2A-H2B dimers and H3-H4 tetramer also show pseudodyad symmetry.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The 4 'core' histones (H2A, H2B, H3 and H4) are relatively similar in structure and are highly conserved through evolution, all featuring a 'helix turn helix turn helix' motif (DNA-binding protein motif that recognize specific DNA sequence).
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] They also share the feature of long 'tails' on one end of the amino acid structure - this being the location of post-translational modification (see below).
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Archaeal histone only contains a H3-H4 like dimeric structure made out of a single type of unit.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Such dimeric structures can stack into a tall superhelix ("hypernucleosome") onto which DNA coils in a manner similar to nucleosome spools.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Only some archaeal histones have tails; tails can also be replaced by a linker joining together two archael histone folds in a single protein chain, thereby giving place to a double histone fold protein.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The distance between the spools around which eukaryotic cells wind their DNA has been determined to range from 59 to 70 Å.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The highly basic nature of histones, aside from facilitating DNA-histone interactions, contributes to their water solubility.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histones are subject to post translational modification by enzymes primarily on their N-terminal tails, but also in their globular domains.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Such modifications include methylation, citrullination, acetylation, phosphorylation, SUMOylation, ubiquitination, and ADP-ribosylation.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This affects their function of gene regulation.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] In general, genes that are active have less bound histone, while inactive genes are highly associated with histones during interphase.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] It also appears that the structure of histones has been evolutionarily conserved, as any deleterious mutations would be severely maladaptive.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] All histones have a highly positively charged N-terminus with many lysine and arginine residues.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Core histones are found in the nuclei of eukaryotic cells and in most Archaeal phyla, but not in bacteria.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The unicellular algae known as dinoflagellates were previously thought to be the only eukaryotes that completely lack histones, but later studies showed that their DNA still encodes histone genes.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Unlike the core histones, homologs of the lysine-rich linker histone (H1) proteins are found in bacteria, otherwise known as nucleoprotein HC1/HC2.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] It has been proposed that core histone proteins are evolutionarily related to the helical part of the extended AAA+ ATPase domain, the C-domain, and to the N-terminal substrate recognition domain of Clp/Hsp100 proteins.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Despite the differences in their topology, these three folds share a homologous helix-strand-helix (HSH) motif.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] It's also proposed that they may have evolved from ribosomal proteins (RPS6/RPS15), both being short and basic proteins.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Archaeal histones may well resemble the evolutionary precursors to eukaryotic histones.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histone proteins are among the most highly conserved proteins in eukaryotes, emphasizing their important role in the biology of the nucleus.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] In contrast mature sperm cells largely use protamines to package their genomic DNA, most likely because this allows them to achieve an even higher packaging ratio.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] There are some *variant* forms in some of the major classes.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] They share amino acid sequence homology and core structural similarity to a specific class of major histones but also have their own feature that is distinct from the major histones.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] These *minor histones* usually carry out specific functions of the chromatin metabolism.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] For example, histone H3-like CENPA is associated with only the centromere region of the chromosome.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histone H2A variant H2A.Z is associated with the promoters of actively transcribed genes and also involved in the prevention of the spread of silent heterochromatin.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Furthermore, H2A.Z has roles in chromatin for genome stability.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Another H2A variant H2A.X is phosphorylated at S139 in regions around double-strand breaks and marks the region undergoing DNA repair.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histone H3.3 is associated with the body of actively transcribed genes.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histones act as spools around which DNA winds.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This enables the compaction necessary to fit the large genomes of eukaryotes inside cell nuclei: the compacted molecule is 40,000 times shorter than an unpacked molecule.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The effect of histones on transcription was established already in the late 1980s.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Specifically, when histones are mutated or depleted a substantial activation of transcription occurs and is independent of other transcription factors (or suggesting that the latter displace histones).
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histones undergo posttranslational modifications that alter their interaction with DNA and nuclear proteins.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The H3 and H4 histones have long tails protruding from the nucleosome, which can be covalently modified at several places.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Modifications of the tail include methylation, acetylation, phosphorylation, ubiquitination, SUMOylation, citrullination, and ADP-ribosylation.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The core of the histones H2A and H2B can also be modified.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Combinations of modifications, known as *histone marks*, are thought to constitute a code, the so-called "histone code".
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histone modifications act in diverse biological processes such as gene regulation, DNA repair, chromosome condensation (mitosis) and spermatogenesis (meiosis).
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] So H3K4me1 denotes the monomethylation of the 4th residue (a lysine) from the start (i.e., the N-terminal) of the H3 protein.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] A huge catalogue of histone modifications have been described, but a functional understanding of most is still lacking.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Collectively, it is thought that histone modifications may underlie a histone code, whereby combinations of histone modifications have specific meanings.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] However, most functional data concerns individual prominent histone modifications that are biochemically amenable to detailed study.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The addition of one, two, or many methyl groups to lysine has little effect on the chemistry of the histone; methylation leaves the charge of the lysine intact and adds a minimal number of atoms so steric interactions are mostly unaffected.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] However, proteins containing Tudor, chromo or PHD domains, amongst others, can recognise lysine methylation with exquisite sensitivity and differentiate mono, di and tri-methyl lysine, to the extent that, for some lysines (e.g.: H4K20) mono, di and tri-methylation appear to have different meanings.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Because of this, lysine methylation tends to be a very informative mark and dominates the known histone modification functions.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Recently it has been shown, that the addition of a serotonin group to the position 5 glutamine of H3, happens in serotonergic cells such as neurons.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This is part of the differentiation of the serotonergic cells.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This post-translational modification happens in conjunction with the H3K4me3 modification.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The serotonylation potentiates the binding of the general transcription factor TFIID to the TATA box.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] What was said above of the chemistry of lysine methylation also applies to arginine methylation, and some protein domains—e.g., Tudor domains—can be specific for methyl arginine instead of methyl lysine.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Arginine is known to be mono- or di-methylated, and methylation can be symmetric or asymmetric, potentially with different meanings.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Enzymes called peptidylarginine deiminases (PADs) hydrolyze the imine group of arginines and attach a keto group, so that there is one less positive charge on the amino acid residue.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This process has been involved in the activation of gene expression by making the modified histones less tightly bound to DNA and thus making the chromatin more accessible.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] PADs can also produce the opposite effect by removing or inhibiting mono-methylation of arginine residues on histones and thus antagonizing the positive effect arginine methylation has on transcriptional activity.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Addition of an acetyl group has a major chemical effect on lysine as it neutralises the positive charge.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This reduces electrostatic attraction between the histone and the negatively charged DNA backbone, loosening the chromatin structure; highly acetylated histones form more accessible chromatin and tend to be associated with active transcription.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Lysine acetylation appears to be less precise in meaning than methylation, in that histone acetyltransferases tend to act on more than one lysine; presumably this reflects the need to alter multiple lysines to have a significant effect on chromatin structure.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Addition of a negatively charged phosphate group can lead to major changes in protein structure, leading to the well-characterised role of phosphorylation in controlling protein function.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] It is not clear what structural implications histone phosphorylation has, but histone phosphorylation has clear functions as a post-translational modification, and binding domains such as BRCT have been characterised.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histone modifications are involved in control of transcription.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Despite the conservation of this complex and histone modification from yeast to mammals, it is not entirely clear what role this modification plays.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] However, it is an excellent mark of active promoters and the level of this histone modification at a gene's promoter is broadly correlated with transcriptional activity of the gene.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] which in turn adds a ubiquitin mark to H2B K123 (K120 in mammals).
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] H2BK123Ub occurs throughout transcribed regions, but this mark is required for COMPASS to trimethylate H3K4 at promoters.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This trimethylation occurs in the body of active genes and is deposited by the methyltransferase Set2.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] , and H3K36Me3 is indicative of actively transcribed genes.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] H3K36Me3 is recognised by the Rpd3 histone deacetylase complex, which removes acetyl modifications from surrounding histones, increasing chromatin compaction and repressing spurious transcription.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Increased chromatin compaction prevents transcription factors from accessing DNA, and reduces the likelihood of new transcription events being initiated within the body of the gene.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This process therefore helps ensure that transcription is not interrupted.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] and is likely bound by other proteins to exert a repressive function.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] and adds the histone modification H2AK119Ub which aids chromatin compaction.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Based on this data it appears that PRC1 is recruited through the action of PRC2, however, recent studies show that PRC1 is recruited to the same sites in the absence of PRC2.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] , and is therefore strongly associated with gene repression.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] although its functional importance remains unclear.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Analysis of histone modifications in embryonic stem cells (and other stem cells) revealed many gene promoters carrying both H3K4Me3 and H3K27Me3, in other words these promoters display both activating and repressing marks simultaneously.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This peculiar combination of modifications marks genes that are poised for transcription; they are not required in stem cells, but are rapidly required after differentiation into some lineages.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Once the cell starts to differentiate, these bivalent promoters are resolved to either active or repressive states depending on the chosen lineage.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Marking sites of DNA damage is an important function for histone modifications.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Without a repair marker, DNA would get destroyed by damage accumulated from sources such as the ultraviolet radiation of the sun.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] H2AX is phosphorylated early after detection of DNA double strand break, and forms a domain extending many kilobases either side of the damage.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] ) and as such, gamma H2AX forms a vital part of the machinery that ensures genome stability.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] H3K56Acx is required for genome stability.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] but is rapidly deacetylated around sites of DNA damage.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] H3K56 acetylation is also required to stabilise stalled replication forks, preventing dangerous replication fork collapses.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Although in general mammals make far greater use of histone modifications than microorganisms, a major role of H3K56Ac in DNA replication exists only in fungi, and this has become a target for antibiotic development.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] phosphorylates histone H3 at serine 10, triggering a cascade of changes that mediate mitotic chromosome condensation.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Condensed chromosomes therefore stain very strongly for this mark, but H3S10 phosphorylation is also present at certain chromosome sites outside mitosis, for example in pericentric heterochromatin of cells during G2.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Phosphorylation of H2B at serine 10 (yeast) or serine 14 (mammals) is also linked to chromatin condensation, but for the very different purpose of mediating chromosome condensation during apoptosis.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This mark is not simply a late acting bystander in apoptosis as yeast carrying mutations of this residue are resistant to hydrogen peroxide-induced apoptotic cell death.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Epigenetic modifications of histone tails in specific regions of the brain are of central importance in addictions.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Once particular epigenetic alterations occur, they appear to be long lasting "molecular scars" that may account for the persistence of addictions.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Cigarette smokers (about 15% of the US population) are usually addicted to nicotine.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] After 7 days of nicotine treatment of mice, acetylation of both histone H3 and histone H4 was increased at the FosB promoter in the nucleus accumbens of the brain, causing 61% increase in FosB expression.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This would also increase expression of the splice variant Delta FosB.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] In the nucleus accumbens of the brain, Delta FosB functions as a "sustained molecular switch" and "master control protein" in the development of an addiction.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] About 7% of the US population is addicted to alcohol.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] In rats exposed to alcohol for up to 5 days, there was an increase in histone 3 lysine 9 acetylation in the pronociceptin promoter in the brain amygdala complex.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This acetylation is an activating mark for pronociceptin.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The nociceptin/nociceptin opioid receptor system is involved in the reinforcing or conditioning effects of alcohol.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Methamphetamine addiction occurs in about 0.2% of the US population.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Chronic methamphetamine use causes methylation of the lysine in position 4 of histone 3 located at the promoters of the *c-fos* and the *C-C chemokine receptor 2 (ccr2)* genes, activating those genes in the nucleus accumbens (NAc). c-fos is well known to be important in addiction.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The *ccr2* gene is also important in addiction, since mutational inactivation of this gene impairs addiction.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histone chaperones are specialized proteins that assist in the proper handling, transport, and assembly of histones, preventing their aggregation and ensuring their appropriate deposition onto DNA.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] These proteins play a crucial role in regulating nucleosome assembly and disassembly, influencing transcriptional activity, DNA replication, and repair.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Unlike enzymatic chromatin remodeling, histone chaperones function by binding histones in a regulated manner, modulating chromatin structure without direct catalytic activity.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] One key function of histone chaperones is maintaining a reservoir of histones, regulating their supply to ensure proper chromatin formation.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] During DNA replication and transcription, histone chaperones such as ASF1 and FACT facilitate nucleosome reassembly, ensuring the preservation of histone modifications that define cellular identity.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Moreover, histone chaperones contribute to nucleosome disassembly in response to cellular stress or DNA damage, thereby allowing access to repair machinery.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histone chaperones also participate in the selective deposition of histone variants, which are functionally distinct from canonical histones.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] For example, HIRA is a chaperone that specifically deposits the histone variant H3.3, a marker of active chromatin regions.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Similarly, CAF-1 is responsible for incorporating H3.1 and H3.2 into newly replicated DNA, highlighting the functional specialization within chaperone networks.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Given their critical roles, misregulation of histone chaperones has been implicated in diseases such as cancer.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Aberrant chaperone activity can lead to improper histone deposition, genome instability, and altered gene expression, contributing to tumorigenesis.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Current research is exploring histone chaperones as potential therapeutic targets, particularly in cancers characterized by disrupted chromatin landscapes.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The coordinated action of multiple histone chaperones forms an intricate network responsible for histone transport, Chromatin assembly factor 1, and genome maintenance.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Chaperone networks facilitate the transport of histones which are synthesized in the cytoplasm and must be escorted to the cell nucleus.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This network ensures histones are deposited at the appropriate genomic locations, maintaining chromatin integrity and function.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histone chaperones play a crucial role in responding to DNA damage by regulating chromatin accessibility.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] For example, in response to double strand breaks, chaperones such as FACT and ASF1 help disassemble nucleosomes at damage sites, allowing repair factors to access the lesion.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Once repair is completed, these chaperones facilitate the reassembly of nucleosomes, restoring chromatin structure and ensuring epigenetic information is maintained.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] In addition to their role in genome stability, histone chaperones contribute to epigenetic inheritance.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] During cell division, chromatin states must be faithfully propagated to daughter cells.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Chaperones help distribute parental histones onto newly synthesized DNA strands, preserving histone modifications and ensuring continuity of cellular identity.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Disruptions in these processes can lead to epigenetic abnormalities associated with developmental disorders.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The first step of chromatin structure duplication is the synthesis of histone proteins: H1, H2A, H2B, H3, H4.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] These proteins are synthesized during S phase of the cell cycle.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] There are different mechanisms which contribute to the increase of histone synthesis.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Yeast carry one or two copies of each histone gene, which are not clustered but rather scattered throughout chromosomes.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histone gene transcription is controlled by multiple gene regulatory proteins such as transcription factors which bind to histone promoter regions.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] In budding yeast, the candidate gene for activation of histone gene expression is SBF.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] SBF is a transcription factor that is activated in late G1 phase, when it dissociates from its repressor Whi5.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This occurs when Whi5 is phosphorylated by Cdc8 which is a G1/S Cdk.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Suppression of histone gene expression outside of S phases is dependent on Hir proteins which form inactive chromatin structure at the locus of histone genes, causing transcriptional activators to be blocked.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] In metazoans the increase in the rate of histone synthesis is due to the increase in processing of pre-mRNA to its mature form as well as decrease in mRNA degradation; this results in an increase of active mRNA for translation of histone proteins.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The mechanism for mRNA activation has been found to be the removal of a segment of the 3' end of the mRNA strand, and is dependent on association with stem-loop binding protein (SLBP).
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] SLBP also stabilizes histone mRNAs during S phase by blocking degradation by the 3'hExo nuclease.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] SLBP levels are controlled by cell-cycle proteins, causing SLBP to accumulate as cells enter S phase and degrade as cells leave S phase.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] SLBP are marked for degradation by phosphorylation at two threonine residues by cyclin dependent kinases, possibly cyclin A/ cdk2, at the end of S phase.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Metazoans also have multiple copies of histone genes clustered on chromosomes which are localized in structures called Cajal bodies as determined by genome-wide chromosome conformation capture analysis (4C-Seq).
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Nuclear protein ataxia-telangiectasia (NPAT), also known as nuclear protein coactivator of histone transcription, is a transcription factor which activates histone gene transcription on chromosomes 1 and 6 of human cells.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] NPAT is also a substrate of cyclin E-Cdk2, which is required for the transition between G1 phase and S phase.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] NPAT activates histone gene expression only after it has been phosphorylated by the G1/S-Cdk cyclin E-Cdk2 in early S phase.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] This shows an important regulatory link between cell-cycle control and histone synthesis.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Histones were discovered in 1884 by Albrecht Kossel.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The word "histone" dates from the late 19th century and is derived from the German word *histon*, a word itself of uncertain origin, perhaps from Ancient Greek *ἵστημι* (hístēmi, "make stand") or *ἱστός* (histós, "loom").
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] In the early 1960s, before the types of histones were known and before histones were known to be highly conserved across taxonomically diverse organisms, James F.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Bonner and his collaborators began a study of these proteins that were known to be tightly associated with the DNA in the nucleus of higher organisms.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Bonner and his postdoctoral fellow Ru Chih C.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Huang showed that isolated chromatin would not support RNA transcription in the test tube, but if the histones were extracted from the chromatin, RNA could be transcribed from the remaining DNA.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Paul T'so and James Bonner had called together a World Congress on Histone Chemistry and Biology in 1964, in which it became clear that there was no consensus on the number of kinds of histone and that no one knew how they would compare when isolated from different organisms.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] For example, they found Histone IV sequence to be highly conserved between peas and calf thymus.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] However, their work on the biochemical characteristics of individual histones did not reveal how the histones interacted with each other or with DNA to which they were tightly bound.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] During the 1980s, Yahli Lorch and Roger Kornberg showed that a nucleosome on a core promoter prevents the initiation of transcription in vitro, and Michael Grunstein demonstrated that histones repress transcription in vivo, leading to the idea of the nucleosome as a general gene repressor.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Relief from repression is believed to involve both histone modification and the action of chromatin-remodeling complexes.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Vincent Allfrey and Alfred Mirsky had earlier proposed a role of histone modification in transcriptional activation, regarded as a molecular manifestation of epigenetics.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] Michael Grunstein and David Allis found support for this proposal, in the importance of histone acetylation for transcription in yeast and the activity of the transcriptional activator Gcn5 as a histone acetyltransferase.
[src:epigenetics/histone-modification] The discovery of the H5 histone appears to date back to the 1970s, and it is now considered an isoform of Histone H1.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The choice of which X chromosome will be inactivated in a particular embryonic cell is random in placental mammals such as humans, but once an X chromosome is inactivated it will remain inactive throughout the lifetime of the cell and its descendants in the organism (its cell line).
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Unlike the random X-inactivation in placental mammals, inactivation in marsupials applies exclusively to the paternally-derived X chromosome.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The paragraphs below have to do only with rodents and do not reflect XI in the majority of mammals.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] X-inactivation is part of the activation cycle of the X chromosome throughout the female life.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The egg and the fertilized zygote initially use maternal transcripts, and the whole embryonic genome is silenced until zygotic genome activation.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Thereafter, all mouse cells undergo an early, imprinted inactivation of the paternally-derived X chromosome in 4–8 cell stage embryos.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The extraembryonic tissues (which give rise to the placenta and other tissues supporting the embryo) retain this early imprinted inactivation, and thus only the maternal X chromosome is active in these tissues.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] In the early blastocyst, this initial, imprinted X-inactivation is reversed in the cells of the inner cell mass (which give rise to the embryo), and in these cells both X chromosomes become active again.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Each of these cells then independently and randomly inactivates one copy of the X chromosome.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] This inactivation event is irreversible during the lifetime of the individual, with the exception of the germline.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] In the female germline before meiotic entry, X-inactivation is reversed, so that after meiosis all haploid oocytes contain a single active X chromosome.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The **Xi** marks the inactive, **Xa** the active X chromosome.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] **XP** denotes the paternal, and **XM** to denotes the maternal X chromosome.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] When the egg (carrying **XM**), is fertilized by a sperm (carrying a Y or an **XP**) a diploid zygote forms.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] **XaM** **XaP** diploid germ cells in meiotic arrest.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] As the meiosis I only completes with ovulation, human germ cells exist in this stage from the first weeks of development until puberty.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] **XaM** AND **XaP** haploid germ cells (eggs).
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The X activation cycle has been best studied in mice, but there are multiple studies in humans.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] As most of the evidence is coming from mice, the above scheme represents the events in mice.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The completion of the meiosis is simplified here for clarity.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Steps 1–4 can be studied in in vitro fertilized embryos, and in differentiating stem cells; X-reactivation happens in the developing embryo, and subsequent (6–7) steps inside the female body, therefore much harder to study.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The descendants of each cell which inactivated a particular X chromosome will also inactivate that same chromosome.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] For an individual cell or lineage the inactivation is therefore skewed or 'non-random', and this can give rise to mild symptoms in female 'carriers' of X-linked genetic disorders.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Typical females possess two X chromosomes, and in any given cell one chromosome will be active (designated as Xa) and one will be inactive (Xi).
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] However, studies of individuals with extra copies of the X chromosome show that in cells with more than two X chromosomes there is still only one Xa, and all the remaining X chromosomes are inactivated.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] This indicates that the default state of the X chromosome in females is inactivation, but one X chromosome is always selected to remain active.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] It is understood that X-chromosome inactivation is a random process, occurring at about the time of gastrulation in the epiblast (cells that will give rise to the embryo).
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The maternal and paternal X chromosomes have an equal probability of inactivation.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] This would suggest that women would be expected to suffer from X-linked disorders approximately 50% as often as men (because women have two X chromosomes, while men have only one); however, in actuality, the occurrence of these disorders in females is much lower than that.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] One explanation for this disparity is that 12–20% of genes on the inactivated X chromosome remain expressed, thus providing women with added protection against defective genes coded by the X-chromosome.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Some suggest that this disparity must be evidence of preferential (non-random) inactivation.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Preferential inactivation of the paternal X-chromosome occurs in both marsupials and in cell lineages that form the membranes surrounding the embryo, whereas in placental mammals either the maternally or the paternally derived X-chromosome may be inactivated in different cell lines.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The time period for X-chromosome inactivation explains this disparity.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Inactivation occurs in the epiblast during gastrulation, which gives rise to the embryo.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Inactivation occurs on a cellular level, resulting in a mosaic expression, in which patches of cells have an inactive maternal X-chromosome, while other patches have an inactive paternal X-chromosome.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] For example, a female heterozygous for haemophilia (an X-linked disease) would have about half of her liver cells functioning properly, which is typically enough to ensure normal blood clotting.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Chance could result in significantly more dysfunctional cells; however, such statistical extremes are unlikely.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Genetic differences on the chromosome may also render one X-chromosome more likely to undergo inactivation.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Also, if one X-chromosome has a mutation hindering its growth or rendering it non viable, cells which randomly inactivated that X will have a selective advantage over cells which randomly inactivated the normal allele.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Thus, although inactivation is initially random, cells that inactivate a normal allele (leaving the mutated allele active) will eventually be overgrown and replaced by functionally normal cells in which nearly all have the same X-chromosome activated.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] It is hypothesized that there is an autosomally-encoded 'blocking factor' which binds to the X chromosome and prevents its inactivation.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The model postulates that there is a limiting blocking factor, so once the available blocking factor molecule binds to one X chromosome the remaining X chromosome(s) are not protected from inactivation.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] This model is supported by the existence of a single Xa in cells with many X chromosomes and by the existence of two active X chromosomes in cell lines with twice the normal number of autosomes.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Sequences at the **X inactivation center** (**XIC**), present on the X chromosome, control the silencing of the X chromosome.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The hypothetical blocking factor is predicted to bind to sequences within the XIC.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The effect of female X heterozygosity is apparent in some localized traits, such as the unique coat pattern of a tortoiseshell cat.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] It can be more difficult, however, to fully understand the expression of un-localized traits in these females, such as the expression of disease.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Since males only have one copy of the X chromosome, all expressed X-chromosomal genes (or alleles, in the case of multiple variant forms for a given gene in the population) are located on that copy of the chromosome.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Females, however, will primarily express the genes or alleles located on the X-chromosomal copy that remains active.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] However, in females that are heterozygous at the causal genes, the inactivation of one copy of the chromosome over the other can have a direct impact on their phenotypic value.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Because of this phenomenon, there is an observed increase in phenotypic variation in females that are heterozygous at the involved gene or genes than in females that are homozygous at that gene or those genes.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] There are many different ways in which the phenotypic variation can play out.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] In many cases, heterozygous females may be asymptomatic or only present minor symptoms of a given disorder, such as with X-linked adrenoleukodystrophy.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The differentiation of phenotype in heterozygous females is furthered by the presence of X-inactivation skewing.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Typically, each X-chromosome is silenced in half of the cells, but this process is skewed when preferential inactivation of a chromosome occurs.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] It is thought that skewing happens either by chance or by a physical characteristic of a chromosome that may cause it to be silenced more or less often, such as an unfavorable mutation.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] On average, each X chromosome is inactivated in half of the cells, although 5-20% of women display X-inactivation skewing.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] In cases where skewing is present, a broad range of symptom expression can occur, resulting in expression varying from minor to severe depending on the skewing proportion.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] An extreme case of this was seen where monozygotic female twins had extreme variance in expression of Menkes disease (an X-linked disorder) resulting in the death of one twin while the other remained asymptomatic.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] It is thought that X-inactivation skewing could be caused by issues in the mechanism that causes inactivation, or by issues in the chromosome itself.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] However, the link between phenotype and skewing is still being questioned, and should be examined on a case-by-case basis.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] A study looking at both symptomatic and asymptomatic females who were heterozygous for Duchenne and Becker muscular dystrophies (DMD) found no apparent link between transcript expression and skewed X-Inactivation.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The study suggests that both mechanisms are independently regulated, and there are other unknown factors at play.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The X-inactivation center (or simply XIC) on the X chromosome is necessary and sufficient to cause X-inactivation.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Chromosomal translocations which place the XIC on an autosome lead to inactivation of the autosome, and X chromosomes lacking the XIC are not inactivated.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The XIC contains four non-translated RNA genes, Xist, Tsix, Jpx and Ftx, which are involved in X-inactivation.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The XIC also contains binding sites for both known and unknown regulatory proteins.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The X-inactive specific transcript (Xist) gene encodes a large non-coding RNA that is responsible for mediating the specific silencing of the X chromosome from which it is transcribed.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The inactive X chromosome is coated by Xist RNA, whereas the Xa is not (See Figure to the right).
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] X chromosomes that lack the Xist gene cannot be inactivated.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Artificially placing and expressing the Xist gene on another chromosome leads to silencing of that chromosome.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Prior to inactivation, both X chromosomes weakly express Xist RNA from the Xist gene.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] During the inactivation process, the future Xa ceases to express Xist, whereas the future Xi dramatically increases Xist RNA production.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] On the future Xi, the Xist RNA progressively coats the chromosome, spreading out from the XIC; the Xist RNA does not localize to the Xa.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The silencing of genes along the Xi occurs soon after coating by Xist RNA.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Like Xist, the Tsix gene encodes a large RNA which is not believed to encode a protein.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The Tsix RNA is transcribed antisense to Xist, meaning that the Tsix gene overlaps the Xist gene and is transcribed on the opposite strand of DNA from the Xist gene.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Tsix is a negative regulator of Xist; X chromosomes lacking Tsix expression (and thus having high levels of Xist transcription) are inactivated much more frequently than normal chromosomes.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Like Xist, prior to inactivation, both X chromosomes weakly express Tsix RNA from the Tsix gene.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Upon the onset of X-inactivation, the future Xi ceases to express Tsix RNA (and increases Xist expression), whereas Xa continues to express Tsix for several days.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Rep A is a long non coding RNA that works with another long non coding RNA, Xist, for X inactivation.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Rep A inhibits the function of Tsix, the antisense of Xist, in conjunction with eliminating expression of Xite.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] It promotes methylation of the Tsix region by attracting PRC2 and thus inactivating one of the X chromosomes.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The inactive X chromosome does not express the majority of its genes, unlike the active X chromosome.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] This is due to the silencing of the Xi by repressive heterochromatin, which compacts the Xi DNA and prevents the expression of most genes.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] PRC2 regulates chromatin compaction and chromatin remodeling in several processes including the DNA damage response.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Additionally, a histone variant called macroH2A (H2AFY) is exclusively found on nucleosomes along the Xi.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] DNA packaged in heterochromatin, such as the Xi, is more condensed than DNA packaged in euchromatin, such as the Xa.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The inactive X forms a discrete body within the nucleus called a Barr body.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The Barr body is generally located on the periphery of the nucleus, is late replicating within the cell cycle, and, as it contains the Xi, contains heterochromatin modifications and the Xist RNA.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] A fraction of the genes along the X chromosome escape inactivation on the Xi.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The Xist gene is expressed at high levels on the Xi and is not expressed on the Xa.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Many other genes escape inactivation; some are expressed equally from the Xa and Xi, and others, while expressed from both chromosomes, are still predominantly expressed from the Xa.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Up to one quarter of genes on the human Xi are capable of escape.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Studies in the mouse suggest that in any given cell type, 3% to 15% of genes escape inactivation, and that escaping gene identity varies between tissues.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Many of the genes which escape inactivation are present along regions of the X chromosome which, unlike the majority of the X chromosome, contain genes also present on the Y chromosome.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] These regions are termed pseudoautosomal regions, as individuals of either sex will receive two copies of every gene in these regions (like an autosome), unlike the majority of genes along the sex chromosomes.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Since individuals of either sex will receive two copies of every gene in a pseudoautosomal region, no dosage compensation is needed for females, so it is postulated that these regions of DNA have evolved mechanisms to escape X-inactivation.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The genes of pseudoautosomal regions of the Xi do not have the typical modifications of the Xi and have little Xist RNA bound.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The existence of genes along the inactive X which are not silenced explains the defects in humans with atypical numbers of the X chromosome, such as Turner syndrome (X0, caused by SHOX gene) or Klinefelter syndrome (XXY).
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Theoretically, X-inactivation should eliminate the differences in gene dosage between affected individuals and individuals with a typical chromosome complement.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] In affected individuals, however, X-inactivation is incomplete and the dosage of these non-silenced genes will differ as they escape X-inactivation, similar to an autosomal aneuploidy.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The precise mechanisms that control escape from X-inactivation are not known, but silenced and escape regions have been shown to have distinct chromatin marks.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] It has been suggested that escape from X-inactivation might be mediated by expression of long non-coding RNA (lncRNA) within the escaping chromosomal domains.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Stanley Michael Gartler used X-chromosome inactivation to demonstrate the clonal origin of cancers.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Examining normal tissues and tumors from females heterozygous for isoenzymes of the sex-linked G6PD gene demonstrated that tumor cells from such individuals express only one form of G6PD, whereas normal tissues are composed of a nearly equal mixture of cells expressing the two different phenotypes.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] This pattern suggests that a single cell, and not a population, grows into a cancer.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] However, this pattern has been proven wrong for many cancer types, suggesting that some cancers may be polyclonal in origin.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Besides, measuring the methylation (inactivation) status of the polymorphic human androgen receptor (HUMARA) located on X-chromosome is considered the most accurate method to assess clonality in female cancer biopsies.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] A great variety of tumors was tested by this method, some, such as renal cell carcinoma, found monoclonal while others (e.g. mesothelioma) were reported polyclonal.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] Researchers have also investigated using X-chromosome inactivation to silence the activity of autosomal chromosomes.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] For example, Jiang *et al.* inserted a copy of the Xist gene into one copy of chromosome 21 in stem cells derived from an individual with trisomy 21 (Down syndrome).
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The inserted Xist gene induces Barr body formation, triggers stable heterochromatin modifications, and silences most of the genes on the extra copy of chromosome 21.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] In these modified stem cells, the Xist-mediated gene silencing seems to reverse some of the defects associated with Down syndrome.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] In 1959, Susumu Ohno showed that the two X chromosomes of mammals were different: one appeared similar to the autosomes; the other was condensed and heterochromatic.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] This finding suggested, independently to two groups of investigators, that one of the X chromosomes underwent inactivation.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] In 1961, Mary Lyon proposed the random inactivation of one female X chromosome to explain the mottled phenotype of female mice heterozygous for coat color genes.
[src:epigenetics/x-inactivation] The Lyon hypothesis also accounted for the findings that one copy of the X chromosome in female cells was highly condensed, and that mice with only one copy of the X chromosome developed as infertile females.
